Title: A Good Girl's Guide to Murder (A Good Girl's Guide to Murder, #1)
Author: Holly  Jackson
My Review: 3.5/5 - Blasted through the book in one night, so I did very much enjoy it, but I suspect that had I taken longer to read it, I would've found the plot and motivations much more of a stretch.

Title: The Gathering Storm (The Wheel of Time, #12)
Author: Robert Jordan
My Review: 3.5/5 - I gave up reading WoT after Winter’s Heart, but with Sanderson finishing the series, I figured I’d actually get around to getting some closure. It doesn’t bode super well that I felt like I didn’t really miss too much despite having skipped two whole books, but it was kind of amazing how quickly I fell back into the universe. A lot of plot actually happens over the course of the book though, which was refreshing. Going to continue reading.

Title: Rhythm of War (The Stormlight Archive, #4)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - While I enjoyed the book more or less the same as the other books in the series, I'm torn as to how I feel about the greater Cosmere coming more into play. This book really starts to weave together details from his other series, which on one hand is pretty cool to see finally come to fruition, but on the other, I don't remember nearly that much about those details, as they've been spread out over so many books and years. Suffice it to say that I'm spending a lot of time on Coppermind after reading this to figure out exactly what's going on.

Title: The Coldest Girl in Coldtown
Author: Holly Black
Publisher: Little, Brown Books for Young Readers
My Review: Liked this alternative(-ish) take on vampires. Had a similar feel to Feed, and I blitzed through this quite quickly and didn't really sweat the details.

Title: How Buildings Learn: What Happens After They're Built
Author: Stewart Brand
My Review: Shockingly relatable to my own field of software development, though still pretty fascinating even if you aren't into building or software architecture. One of the better arguments for agile that I've ever read.

Title: Ghost (Track, #1)
Author: Jason  Reynolds
My Review: It was fine - quite predictable and not terribly deep, but nice.

Title: Lobizona (Wolves of No World, #1)
Author: Romina Garber
My Review: Not too much to note here - an enjoyable read, and good enough that I actually do want to read the sequel.

Title: Shape Up: Stop Running in Circles and Ship Work that Matters
Author: Ryan Singer

Title: Everything, Everything
Author: Nicola Yoon
My Review: 2.5/5 - Enjoyable writing, but didn't love the child abuse twist and casually ableist conclusion.

Title: Property-Based Testing in a Screencast Editor
Author: Oskar Wickström
My Review: I'm not really sure who this book is for, but I thought it was a good skim. There's good food for thought on using PBT on a real application. The code samples were somewhat obtuse for me, as I'm hardly fluent in Haskell. The scenarios make sense, though there is some amount of assumption that the codebase is already quite testable, which is probably fair.

Title: Shuri (2018-) #1
Author: Nnedi Okorafor
Additional Authors: Leonardo Romero, Sam Spratt, Jordie Bellaire

Title: Rise of the Black Panther (2018) #6 (of 6)
Author: Ta-Nehisi Coates

Author: Ta-Nehisi Coates

Author: Jason Aaron

Title: Black Panther (2005-2008) #39
Author: Jason Aaron
Additional Authors: Jefte Palo, Lee Loughridge, Cory Petit

Title: Security (Logic #10)
Author: Ben Tarnoff
Additional Authors: Moira Weigel, Jen Kagan, Alex Blasdel

Title: The Long Way to a Small, Angry Planet (Wayfarers, #1)
Author: Becky Chambers
My Review: A fun read, more fun than most. I enjoyed the pace and that it threw about one weird culture shock moment per chapter at the reader. Though most of the culture shocks were relatively tame and not especially novel, they were still fun. The novel kind of skims over some of the weightier issues, but it felt appropriate for the tone.

Title: If You Come Softly
Author: Jacqueline Woodson
My Review:
It was good, but I didn't really need another sad story about a black youth losing their life right now.

I also don't love "love at first sight".

All that being said, it's horrifying that this was written *20 years ago* and nothing has seemingly changed. (And embarrassing how unaware I was at that point in time.)

Title: East of West, Vol. 9
Author: Jonathan Hickman
Additional Authors: Nick Dragotta, Frank Martin, Rus Wooton

Title: The Tyrant Baru Cormorant (The Masquerade, #3)
Author: Seth Dickinson
My Review: 3.5/5 - Oof, this was a long road to go down for a pretty reasonable payoff. I kind of thought this would be the last book in the series, but apparently not? I did find the plot armor to be quite abused by the plot, but overall, I still enjoyed the action and culture criticisms posed by the book.

Title: Deathless Divide (Dread Nation, #2)
Author: Justina Ireland
My Review: 3.5/5 - Enjoyed it and blew through it in very few sittings, but not as compelling as the first book. Some of the character turns between the first and second book struck me as somewhat jarring. Still, a satisfying finish to where the first book left off and Jane's arc certainly felt appropriate.

Title: It Wasn't Me
Author: Dana Alison Levy
My Review: I was skeptical that I'd like it when I started, but the writing had just the right amount of whimsy and drew me in!

Title: A Philosophy of Software Design
Author: John Ousterhout
Private Notes: Recommended by lots of people on this thread: https://twitter.com/drmaciver/status/1264943084607021057

Title: Making Software: What Really Works, and Why We Believe It
Author: Andy Oram

Title: Debugging: The 9 Indispensable Rules for Finding Even the Most Elusive Software and Hardware Problems
Author: David J. Agans

Title: Thinking in Bets: Making Smarter Decisions When You Don't Have All the Facts
Author: Annie Duke

Title: The Biggest Bluff: How I Learned to Pay Attention, Master Myself, and Win
Author: Maria Konnikova

Title: Invisible Women: Data Bias in a World Designed for Men
Author: Caroline Criado Pérez

Title: A Fire Upon the Deep (Zones of Thought, #1)
Author: Vernor Vinge

Title: The Last Emperox (The Interdependency, #3)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: One of the very few books that was *too* fast-paced for my taste! While I do appreciate novels that aren't bloated (as so many are nowadays), I actually would've preferred a little more time and development in this case. The wrapping up of all the plot threads was nicely done, but fell a bit flat due to how quickly the character development moved. Still, the pace and plot together meant that I blew through this book and it was a fine ending for the series.

Title: Dread Nation (Dread Nation, #1)
Author: Justina Ireland
My Review: This was great. While I like a lot of our YA book club choices, this is one of the few where I've gone out and actually put a hold on the next book to read. One thing I especially appreciated was how normal the main characters were - they were skilled due to their education, not inherently talented at zombie killing.

Title: So You Want to Talk About Race
Author: Ijeoma Oluo
My Review: Unquestionably 5/5. I started this book sometime last year for our work book club, but circumstances made it difficult to attend meetings and I only just got around to sitting down and finishing the last third. This is basically “Racism 101”, and a fantastic resource for anyone who’s unfamiliar with the territory. A must read for those who are just now hearing all this unfamiliar terminology, though you’ll likely need to set aside your ego and pride to really be open to understanding.

Title: Shadows of Sherwood (Robyn Hoodlum, #1)
Author: Kekla Magoon
My Review: Fun, liked it, didn’t love it. Had a hard time getting past the idea that the protagonist was 12, but maybe that’s since I went in expecting more YA than children’s.

Title: The Westing Game
Author: Ellen Raskin
My Review: This was my book club book choice after watching Knives Out, which reminded me of The Westing Game. I didn’t remember anything about the actual plot though, only that I enjoyed this as a child. On the re-read, it turned out that I still liked the book a lot, although it did feel very dated throughout.

Title: Once & Future, Vol. 1: The King is Undead
Author: Kieron Gillen

Title: Bodies (Logic #8)
Author: Ben Tarnoff
Additional Authors: Moira Weigel, Alex Blasdel, Jen Kagan
My Review: 4.5/5 - Can’t believe it took me so long to subscribe to Logic! Overall, fantastic and thought-provoking content, and the handfeel was as good as I had heard. Looking forward to continuing my subscription and if anyone wants to borrow any issues to check it out, let me know.

Title: Tales from the DC Dark Multiverse
Author: Scott Snyder
Additional Authors: Kyle Higgins, Jeff Loveness, Tim Seeley, James Tynion IV, Mat Groom, Javier  Fernández, Brad Walker, Drew Hennessy, Norm Rapmund, Kyle Hotz, Dexter Vines, Walden Wong, Danny Miki, Aaron Lopresti, Matt Ryan, Tom Raney

Title: Immortal Hulk, Volume 3: Hulk In Hell
Author: Al Ewing
Additional Authors: Joe Bennett, Kyle Hotz, Eric Nguyen, Ruy Jose

Title: Revenant Gun (The Machineries of Empire, #3)
Author: Yoon Ha Lee
My Review: Similarly meh to the sequel. A satisfactory ending to the trilogy, but both this and the previous book felt very "deus ex machina" in the plotting. The calendrical system was cleverly used in the first book, but didn't really add much to these last two.

Title: Raven Stratagem (The Machineries of Empire, #2)
Author: Yoon Ha Lee
My Review: Didn’t enjoy this as much as the first book. The first book asked for a significant suspension of belief for the calendrical system, but while the sequel dials that back, I wound up needing to suspend even more for the plot. Overall, kind of meh, but I’ll probably finish off the trilogy nonetheless since it’s pretty nice reading.

Title: Ninefox Gambit (The Machineries of Empire, #1)
Author: Yoon Ha Lee
My Review:
Loved the bizarre world with calendrical technology. Appreciated that it was left very unexplained, but I could've used just a *bit* more explanation of the world. I also didn't entirely buy Jedao's inexplicable military greatness, but definitely good enough for a romping tale.

You do have to just accept the "calendrical" universe at face value, but I had no problem doing that.

Title: Battle Royale
Author: Koushun Takami
My Review: I wasn’t sure I’d like it and was somewhat put off by the thickness of the book, but I wound up devouring it in a day. The sheer number of characters you meet in the initial setup was also intimidating, but most of them are killed off before you really need to know who they are.

Title: The Batman Who Laughs
Author: Scott Snyder
Additional Authors: James Tynion IV, Jock, Eduardo Risso, David Baron

Title: Railsea
Author: China Miéville
My Review: A fun read, with a lot of character to the world. Blitzed through it pretty quickly, and although it left me very curious about the history of the world, it's surely better left to the imagination than over-explained.

Title: Nature (Logic #9)
Author: Ben Tarnoff
Additional Authors: Moira Weigel, Alex Blasdel, Jen Kagan
My Review: As always, Logic is thought-provoking collection of work that's well worth reading. Let me know if you want to borrow it!

Title: This Is How You Lose the Time War
Author: Amal El-Mohtar
My Review: 4.5/5 - A beautiful read. Only partly my usual fare, in that it’s nominally SFF, and I don’t usually read for language and words, but I loved it! Nice and short, would highly recommend if you’re into either of the above.

Title: The Mysterious Howling (The Incorrigible Children of Ashton Place #1)
Author: Maryrose Wood
My Review: The writing was delightful and the overall story a lot of fun. I wish I had realized it was more J than YA when I was reading it, as I think my expectations would've been better set. I don't love that we hit the end of the book (with the requisite cliffhanger) right as we got to the meat of the story, though. Really felt more like the first few chapters of a longer story rather than a full book by itself.

Title: Starsight (Skyward, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - A solid sequel to Skyward. Sanderson's plucky hero(in)es are getting a little stale for me, but I'm as into the plotting and morality as much as I always have and still read the book in a night, so enjoyed it a lot anyway.

Title: Exhalation: Stories
Author: Ted Chiang
My Review: 3.5/5 - I think perhaps my expectations were set too high from Ted Chiang's previous collection. That, and I had already read a few of these stories somewhere else. Still, lovely reads and I blew through it pretty quickly (probably since a few were already familiar from past reading).

Title: Unnatural, Vol. 1: Awakening
Author: Mirka Andolfo
Additional Authors: Milo Manara, Stanley "Artgerm" Lau, Matteo Scalera, Bengal

Title: Immortal Hulk, Volume 2: The Green Door
Author: Al Ewing
Additional Authors: Joe Bennett, Lee Garbett, Martin Simmonds

Title: Immortal Hulk, Volume 1: Or is he Both?
Author: Al Ewing

Title: The Mighty Thor, Volume 1: Thunder in Her Veins
Author: Jason Aaron

Title: Coda #4
Author: Simon Spurrier
Additional Authors: Matías Bergara, Michael Doig, Laura Allred

Title: Dreamland Burning
Author: Jennifer Latham
Publisher: Little, Brown Books for Young Readers
My Review: 3.5/5 - An educational book - I had never heard of the Tulsa race riots before, so worth reading just for that, if nothing else. It was a somewhat emotionally tough read, and though a part of me dreads confronting the past, I was able to get through it nonetheless and appreciated it.

Title: 9 Out of 10 Climbers Make the Same Mistakes
Author: Dave MacLeod
My Review: 3.5/5 - Not a lot that was really new or surprising for me, but supports a lot of what I previously had read, and has a lot of generally good advice if you aren’t already somewhat into athletic performance.

Title: Empress of Forever
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review: 4.5/5 - One of the most enjoyable books I’ve read in a little while, as it definitely checks all the boxes for me. The setting (and overall tech level of the universe) reminds me a bit of A Fire Upon the Deep.

Title: Tiamat's Wrath (The Expanse, #8)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: Still looking forward to more books in the Expanse series, so still pretty damn good.

Title: The Consuming Fire (The Interdependency, #2)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: Liked it more than the first book, but it's not really wow-ing me. Still, a pretty fast and light read, so maybe the next book will be good plane reading?

Title: A Blade So Black (Nightmare-Verse, #1)
Author: L.L. McKinney
My Review: I had high hopes from the beginning, when the author immediately jumps into the action and skips over the training montage, but it fell short of my expectations by the middle of the book. There’s a lot of potential, but overall, I’m not particularly interested in the sequel, despite the book being only the first half of the story.

Title: The Monster Baru Cormorant (The Masquerade, #2)
Author: Seth Dickinson
My Review:
A good follow up to the previous book. Pretty much got exactly what I expected and wanted!

That being said, while it was nice to have other characters at Baru’s level, I do hope she gets some more growth in the next book. She wallows in her weakness in this book, and I think that’s enough for me.

Title: All Systems Red (The Murderbot Diaries, #1)
Author: Martha Wells
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun and fast read.

Title: Skyward (Skyward, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun read, but I enjoyed Sanderson’s other YA books more, and the snarky hero bit started to wear on me.

Title: Creative Selection: Inside Apple's Design Process During the Golden Age of Steve Jobs
Author: Ken Kocienda
My Review: 4.5/5 - This was a fantastic read. I'd highly recommend it if you're at all interested in Apple and/or developing software. The author really captures what programming is like (at least for me), if you're at all interested in a glimpse of that. I particularly enjoyed a look behind the curtain at initial iPhone development, having worked in Windows Mobile during that timeframe.

Title: The Wild Storm, Vol. 1
Author: Warren Ellis
Additional Authors: Jon Davis-Hunt, Steve Buccellato, Ivan Plascencia, John Kalisz, Simon Bowland

Title: East of West, Vol. 7
Author: Jonathan Hickman

Author: Jonathan Hickman

Author: Jonathan Hickman

Title: East of West, Vol. 1: The Promise
Author: Jonathan Hickman
Additional Authors: Nick Dragotta, Frank Martin, Rus Wooton

Title: The Poppy War (The Poppy War, #1)
Author: R.F. Kuang
My Review: Reading this was a lot like reading The Magicians. Loved the premise, the world, and the beginning of the story. (A bit Mary Sue-ish, but I kind of like that sort of story anyway.) The middle and end of the plot fell kind of flat, though.

Title: The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl, Vol. 1: Squirrel Power
Author: Ryan North
Additional Authors: Erica Henderson, Maris Wicks, Kyle Starks, Chris Giarrusso, Rico Renzi, Wil Moss

Title: Rat Queens: Deluxe Edition, Volume 1
Author: Kurtis J. Wiebe
Additional Authors: Roc Upchurch, Tess Fowler, Stjepan Šejić

Title: Seven to Eternity, Vol. 2: Ballad of Betrayal
Author: Rick Remender

Title: Seven to Eternity, Vol. 1: The God of Whispers
Author: Rick Remender
Additional Authors: Jerome Opeña, Matt Hollingsworth, Rus Wooton

Title: Godshaper
Author: Simon Spurrier
My Review: 4.5/5 - Really dug everything about this. Gorgeous art, super interesting universe, solid characters, and a fantastic plot. I especially love that it’s a complete story and not everything is explained at the end.

Title: Because You Love to Hate Me: 13 Tales of Villainy
Author: Amerie
Additional Authors: Renée Ahdieh, Soman Chainani, Susan Dennard, Sarah Enni, Marissa Meyer, Cindy Pon, Victoria Schwab, Samantha Shannon, Adam Silvera, Andrew  Smith, April Genevieve Tucholke, Nicola Yoon, Sasha Alsberg, Whitney Atkinson, Tina Burke, Catriona Feeney, Jesse George, Zoë Herdt, Samantha Lane, Sophia  Lee, Raeleen Lemay, Regan Perusse, Christine Riccio, Steph Sinclair, Kat  Kennedy, Ben Alderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - Lots of really great short stories in here, although I’m not entirely sure the booktubers really contributed much. The prompts for the stories were all over the place and I found almost all of the interludes from the booktubers to be rather cringey. Maybe that’s just me being old and cranky. A couple of weaker stories, but overall a fun read.

Title: IBM and the Holocaust: The Strategic Alliance Between Nazi Germany and America's Most Powerful Corporation-Expanded Edition
Author: Edwin Black

Title: The Woman Who Smashed Codes: A True Story of Love, Spies, and the Unlikely Heroine who Outwitted America's Enemies
Author: Jason Fagone
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun read, especially if you're into history (WWII in particular) and/or cryptography. I appreciated learning about the hidden history of Elizebeth Friedman. Would also recommend [b:The Code Book: The Science of Secrecy from Ancient Egypt to Quantum Cryptography|17994|The Code Book  The Science of Secrecy from Ancient Egypt to Quantum Cryptography|Simon Singh|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1403181687s/17994.jpg|1031975] if you want more depth on the cryptography.

Title: The Freeze-Frame Revolution
Author: Peter Watts
My Review: A pretty fun read, but I did not like this as much as Watts' other works. Might be a 3.5 or 4 if I weren't comparing it to Blindsight, etc.

Title: Radical Candor: Be a Kickass Boss Without Losing Your Humanity
Author: Kim Malone Scott
My Review:
While I largely agreed with the content, I had a hard time with the author's personality/writing style, as the book reeked of both privilege and a Silicon Valley mindset that I don't particularly agree with. (See my highlights for examples.) I'm not sure the book has much more to add to the concept than what you can find online in blog posts.

That being said, I stopped halfway through the book since the second half appeared to be primarily aimed at managers, which I am not. So there may very well be valuable nuggets of wisdom/advice that I skipped out on.

Title: Exercises in Programming Style
Author: Cristina Videira Lopes
My Review:
I think this would’ve been a much more interesting read several years ago for me, when I was far less experienced and knew much less about different programming languages/patterns. Even so, I think this would be a fantastic reference for getting re-familiarized with concepts presented in the book. I absolutely love how the author uses Python throughout the book as a reference sample for each new idea.

Would highly recommend for programmers that haven’t seen a lot of these styles before.

Title: Accelerate: Building and Scaling High-Performing Technology Organizations
Author: Nicole Forsgren
My Review: 4.5/5 - Nothing too surprising for me, which itself is not terribly surprising, given my own biases in this area. I'd definitely recommend this for anyone who doesn't work in an org that does devops well and/or needs support for moving towards a more agile process. That being said, if you're interested at all, I'd check this out, since it was such a smooth, straightforward, and no-nonsense read. Also, if you're already mostly familiar with the topic, then it's probably safe to skip forward to Appendix B to get the meat more succinctly.

Title: Akata Witch (Akata Witch, #1)
Author: Nnedi Okorafor
My Review: 3.5/5 - My feelings for the book largely echo how I felt about Black Panther in that I absolutely loved the texture and flavor, even if some of the other parts of the story were lacking. I am keen on learning more about this world, although the Gladstone fan in me wonders how the heck the economy works!

Title: The Metabarons: Ultimate Collection
Author: Alejandro Jodorowsky
My Review: A fascinating universe, but quite difficult to get past the misogyny. Unless you're really into Jodorowsky and the weirdness that is the Metabarons universe, probably not worth digging into.

Title: Persepolis Rising (The Expanse, #7)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: I was skeptical for the first third or so of the book, but by the end, was re-intrigued by the universe. I quite like how the authors keep shaking up the status quo, and I really hope there's a decent wrap-up by the end of this series...

Title: Shadow and Bone (The Shadow and Bone Trilogy, #1)
Author: Leigh Bardugo
My Review: Fun but kind of forgettable. The setting was enjoyable, but the characters pretty flat and the plot rather straightforward.

Title: The Will to Battle (Terra Ignota, #3)
Author: Ada Palmer
My Review: 3.5/5 - Such a strange series... I'm still drawn in by the writing and concepts, although some of it the affections are wearing thin by now. All in all, I'm still interested enough to read the last book in the series, but I'm not sure I'd make the same decision if it weren't going to be the last.

Title: Snapshot
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Short and fun, though I think Sanderson's strengths in plotting and worldbuilding are not fully utilized in the short story format.

Title: Oathbringer (The Stormlight Archive, #3)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
What can I say? If you like Sanderson's other work, you'll like this book. As usual, it makes me want to reread the other books in the series, but I'm not going to since they're a bazillion pages long and I have enough other stuff to read as it is. Sigh.

Also of note: this is the first Sanderson book that has a strong enough tie to the rest of the Cosmere that I also want to reread one of the books outside of the Stormlight Archive. (Keeping it generic to avoid spoilers!)

Now back to waiting for more Sanderson books...

Title: When Dimple Met Rishi (Dimple and Rishi, #1)
Author: Sandhya Menon
My Review: Even though I thought the plot and characters were rather contrived and thin, I still somehow found myself enjoying the read nonetheless. I also found the ending rather pat and also had serious reservations around the startup culture worship in the book (seriously, Insomnia Con? 🤮). That being said though, I'm interested in reading more from this author in the future.

Title: An Astronaut's Guide to Life on Earth
Author: Chris Hadfield
My Review: Really fun and fast read. Hadfield does a wonderful job sprinkling in random tidbits about being an astronaut throughout the book, and although he does touch upon how his career choice was difficult for his family, I'm now more curious to hear about it from their perspective!

Title: Red Rising (Red Rising Saga, #1)
Author: Pierce Brown
My Review: A fun read, but requires quite a bit of suspension of disbelief and more than a few times felt somewhat "Mary Sue"-ish. Overall, I preferred Baru Cormorant's more nuanced take on bringing down the system from the inside, even though this was entertaining.

Title: Beautiful Racket
Author: Matthew Butterick
My Review:
Enjoyed the book overall. Definitely one of the better written programming books out there, although I'm not sure the author succeeded in targeting the book for relatively new programmers! It was a pleasure to go through the tutorials and explanations, but there's a lot of content packed into each section and requires active attention and thought throughout.

4.5 for the content and delivery, but 4 overall since I'm not sure at all what personal projects this might be useful for in the future.

Title: Turn the Ship Around!: A True Story of Turning Followers into Leaders
Author: L. David Marquet
My Review: Unsurprisingly, quite liked this book as it aligns very much with my leadership/management preferences and beliefs. The subject matter also helped, as it was interesting to get peeks into the workings of a nuclear submarine as a backdrop for the discussion around leadership. It's certainly very compelling, and although there are certainly differences when applying this style in non-military organizations, there's still lots of useful thoughts in here.

Title: The Hate U Give (The Hate U Give, #1)
Author: Angie Thomas
My Review: 4.5/5 - Super emotionally draining, but an exceptional read.

Title: Longitude: The True Story of a Lone Genius Who Solved the Greatest Scientific Problem of His Time
Author: Dava Sobel
My Review: A delightful read for anyone that has a passing interest in timekeeping, even more so since it's so short! I only wish it had pictures and diagrams.

Title: The Ruin of Angels (Craft Sequence, #6)
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review: Enjoyed the book, although not quite as much as previous Craft novels. The general feeling of the book reminded of The City and the City and the City of X series. This is by no means a bad thing, but dulled the base conceit a bit. Still, I'm looking forward to more books in this Sequence.

Title: The Stone Sky (The Broken Earth, #3)
Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review: Didn't love this as much as the first two books, but a worthy end to the trilogy.

Title: Existence
Author: David Brin
My Review: Really liked the overall concepts and ideas in the book, but wasn't a huge fan of the slow first half and random time jumps in the second half. Lots of interesting threads that perhaps could've been better served with more time/focus rather than jamming all of them into a single book?

Title: Ultimate Glory: Frisbee, Obsession, and My Wild Youth
Author: David Gessner
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun read about ultimate in the 80's (-ish). Definitely worth checking out if you're into ultimate, but I don't know if it would be interesting for non-players...

Title: How to Bake Pi: An Edible Exploration of the Mathematics of Mathematics
Author: Eugenia Cheng
My Review: Very enjoyable book. Didn't get as much about category theory that I wanted, but turned out that the parts not about category theory were still pretty great. Still, it was nice to get another fresh angle on the subject with lots of analogies.

Title: Seven Surrenders (Terra Ignota, #2)
Author: Ada Palmer
My Review: These books are the kind where if I miss a page, I actually need to go back and re-read it. I'm still not quite sure why I enjoyed reading Terra Ignota as much as I have, but ¯\_(ツ)_/¯. There are definitely bits that remind me of Dune, the plot meanders in ways that I completely don't expect, and the treatment of sexuality/religion is interesting as well.

Title: The Collapsing Empire (The Interdependency, #1)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: Fun, but didn't really feel like much actually happened in the book. Will likely read the next two or three books since it was an easy read and I'm curious about the overall story arc.

Title: City of Miracles (The Divine Cities, #3)
Author: Robert Jackson Bennett
My Review: A fantastic end to the trilogy. Reading both this and City of Blades really makes me want to go back and re-read City of Stairs again. I felt like overall, there wasn't a ton of new concepts in the genre of warring divinities affected by their worshippers, but even still, I really enjoyed the read.

Title: Thrawn (Star Wars: Thrawn, #1)
Author: Timothy Zahn
My Review: I was a little worried about reading this, since not all media I loved in my youth has held up to later reading/viewing, but it turned out okay in the end. Thrawn was a mix of Sherlock Holmes and Game of Thrones in space, and while I do love me some brains and politics, it fell somewhat short in several ways. First, since this is a prequel novel, there's never any particular threat to Thrawn since you know where he winds up, and second, he never really changes as a character. He starts out as a badass and is pretty much a badass throughout the book. Still, an enjoyable and light read.

Title: Babylon's Ashes (The Expanse, #6)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: Satisfying, although not quite as gripping to me as the previous couple books. The ending actually felt like a solid ending though, and although I'm quite happy that there will be more books, I could also see the series ending after this one.

Title: Laurinda
Author: Alice Pung
My Review: Liked the book and despite not having as much of a culture gap as Lucy, much of her issues acclimating to her new environment felt very familiar to me.

Title: The Obelisk Gate (The Broken Earth, #2)
Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review: I think I liked the first one more, but this was still excellent and I can't wait for the last book.

Title: The Fifth Season (The Broken Earth, #1)
Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review: 4.5/5 - I finally gave in after seeing this book on just about every end-of-year book list. Glad I did - it lived up to the hype.

Title: Death's End (Remembrance of Earth’s Past, #3)
Author: Liu Cixin
My Review: Much better than the second in the series. I'm a sucker for books that span eons and galaxies (Forever War, Fire Upon the Deep, etc.), and this hit the spot. There's a bit of deus ex machina with regards to the science, and I would've loved to zoom out from the protagonists, as it were, but it was still lovely nonetheless.

Title: The Edge: The War against Cheating and Corruption in the Cutthroat World of Elite Sports
Author: Roger Pielke
My Review: Kind of a slog to get through, but some interesting thoughts around solutions to some of these problems in modern sports. Definitely some meat to chew on in regards to ultimate's "spirit of the game".

Title: Speaking American: How Y'all, Youse, and You Guys Talk: A Visual Guide
Author: Josh Katz
My Review: Quick and fun read. Nice map infographics in a dead-tree format, but not too different than the online presentation.

Title: Calamity (Reckoners, #3)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
A fun read, but ultimately left me with more questions than answers. The end felt entirely too abrupt, too.

If you liked it though, I'd also highly recommend Worm (https://parahumans.wordpress.com/), an absurdly long web serial that covers similar ground.

Title: The Three-Body Problem (Remembrance of Earth’s Past #1)
Author: Liu Cixin
My Review: An interesting concept, although I found the third act to be somewhat weak. The infodump at the end was a bit much, and the lead up to the reveal also a bit confused. Still, I like the concept enough to at least give the sequel a shot. Also, it reminds me quite a lot of The Mote in God's Eye.

Title: Ancillary Mercy (Imperial Radch, #3)
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review: Liked reading it, but felt a bit underwhelming compared to the previous books. The way the plot goes in this book kept reminding me of the Culture.

Title: Uprooted
Author: Naomi Novik
My Review: 4.5/5 - Just devoured this book.

Title: Two Hours: The Quest to Run the Impossible Marathon
Author: Ed Caesar
My Review: An enjoyable although light read, mainly since I don't follow professional running and it was neat to get a glimpse into that world.

Title: Shadowshaper (Shadowshaper, #1)
Author: Daniel José Older
My Review: 2.5/5 - Felt like it needed more editing? Liked the non-fantasy parts a lot, and while the concept of shadowshaping was quite neat, I thought the plot and universe really didn't back it up. Still, a quick read that was pretty fun.

Title: The View from the O-Line: Football According to NFL Offensive Linemen and an Uncommon Coach
Author: Howard Mudd
My Review: I blew through this book, which was mostly a collection of thoughts from offensive linemen. From the description alone, you should probably already know whether you're going to like this book or not.

Title: Badass: Making Users Awesome
Author: Kathy Sierra
My Review: Considering how much I <3 Kathy Sierra's other works, I was surprised to kind of bounce off this book. I thought that the content was good, but I couldn't relate very much to the concepts and it moved too slowly for my personal use case.

Title: Winter (The Lunar Chronicles, #4)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review: Enjoyed this much more than the last couple books in the series! The ending is a little pat, but understandable given the fairy tale inspiration.

Title: Cress (The Lunar Chronicles, #3)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review: So far, the series is interesting/fun enough for me to continue reading, but mostly since it's YA and really easy to get through.

Title: Shrill: Notes from a Loud Woman
Author: Lindy West
My Review: Interesting book for me to rate/review. One of the few books that I rated higher than I actually liked the book. Not that I disliked it, but in this case, the content bumped the book up to a four from what probably would've been a 3.5.

Title: Four Roads Cross (Craft Sequence, #5)
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review: 3.5/5 - While I still really love the concept and universe, the plot felt a bit thin. Lots of stuff randomly (to me, at least) happening and not really given enough room to breathe. Still though, I tore through it in a couple of days, so obviously it wasn't that much of a problem.

Title: Six-Gun Snow White
Author: Catherynne M. Valente
My Review: Finished this mainly since it was so short.

Title: Hamilton: The Revolution
Author: Lin-Manuel Miranda
My Review: 4.5/5 - Probably required reading for anyone who loves the musical. Well put together, and loads of interesting behind-the-scenes information. It's also just an absolutely lovely physical book.

Title: Scarlet (The Lunar Chronicles, #2)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review: Enjoyed reading it, but it wasn't as captivating as Cinder.

Title: Bitch Planet, Vol. 1: Extraordinary Machine (Bitch Planet Collected Editions, #1)
Author: Kelly Sue DeConnick
Additional Authors: Taki Soma, Valentine De Landro, Robert Wilson IV, Cris Peter, Clayton Cowles, Lauren Sankovitch

Title: Between the World and Me
Author: Ta-Nehisi Coates
My Review: 4.5/5 - A powerful and difficult read. Almost a must-read for, well, pretty much anyone.

Title: Too Like the Lightning (Terra Ignota, #1)
Author: Ada Palmer
My Review: Kind of torn about this book. It wasn't easy reading, but a fascinating world and intriguing concepts kept me interested throughout. The play on gendered language reminds me of Ancillary Mercy, but I had quite a lot more difficulty with it here (not in a bad way!). I kind of can't wait to see what the sequel holds in store, but it was annoying that it pretty much just leaves the reader at a cliffhanger.

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender- Smoke and Shadow, Part 3 (Smoke and Shadow, #3)
Author: Gene Luen Yang

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - Smoke and Shadow, Part 2 (Smoke and Shadow, #2)
Author: Gene Luen Yang

Title: The Sudden Appearance of Hope
Author: Claire North
My Review: I really liked this book, although at the end of it, I can't quite put my finger on why. I think the concept is quite novel, and everything that happens actually more or less makes sense in context of people forgetting Hope. That, combined with the mystery/action/heist/sci-fi just kind of hit all the right notes for me.

Title: Cinder (The Lunar Chronicles, #1)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review: An enjoyable, although predictable, read.

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - Smoke and Shadow, Part 1 (Smoke and Shadow, #1)
Author: Gene Luen Yang

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender: The Rift, Part 3 (The Rift, #3)
Author: Gene Luen Yang

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Rift, Part 2 (The Rift, #2)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Rift, Part 1 (The Rift, #1)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko, Gurihiru

Title: The Tattooed Potato and Other Clues
Author: Ellen Raskin
My Review: I liked it, even though it required quite a bit of suspension of disbelief.

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Search, Part 3 (The Search, #3)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Search, Part 1 (The Search, #1)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Bryan Konietzko, Michael Dante DiMartino, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Search, Part 2 (The Search, #2)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Promise, Part 3 (The Promise, #3)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Promise, Part 2 (The Promise, #2)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender - The Promise, Part 1 (The Promise, #1)
Author: Gene Luen Yang
Additional Authors: Bryan Konietzko, Michael Dante DiMartino, Gurihiru

Title: Avatar: The Last Airbender: The Lost Adventures (Avatar: The Last Airbender)
Author: Bryan Konietzko
Additional Authors: Michael Dante DiMartino, Aaron Ehasz, Alison Wilgus, Amy Kim Ganter, Brian Ralph, Corey Lewis, Dave Roman, Elsa Garagarza, Ethan Spaulding, Frank Pittarese, Gurihiru, J. Torres, Joaquim Dos Santos, Johane Matte, John O'Bryan, Joshua Hamilton, Justin Ridge, Kaite Mattila, May Chan, Rawles Marie Lumumba, Reagan Lodge, Tim Hedrick, Tom McWeeney

Title: The Dark Forest (Remembrance of Earth’s Past, #2)
Author: Liu Cixin
My Review: 2.5/5 - Meh. Figured out the winning strategy almost immediately. The other Wallfacer strategies were intriguing, but the book felt kind of all over the place. Not sure I'll read the third book.

Title: If You Could Be Mine
Author: Sara Farizan
My Review: I liked the overall themes of the book, dealing with LGBT issues as teenagers in Iran, but I really couldn't get over how idiotic the main characters were.

Title: City of Blades (The Divine Cities, #2)
Author: Robert Jackson Bennett
My Review: 4.5/5 - I don't remember much from the first book, but this makes me want to go back and reread it, which is probably a pretty good sign! An excellent read with really enjoyable characters.

Title: The Peripheral (The Peripheral #1)
Author: William Gibson
My Review: 2.5/5 - Liked the stub concept and the characters, but it was overall a slog to get through. The plot felt rather thin and it was not a really easy read. I was tempted to give up on it more than once, but it was just good enough for me to stick with it.

Title: A Monster Calls
Author: Patrick Ness
My Review: A lovely read despite its predictability. Awfully sad, though - I can't quite believe it's YA.

Title: Secret History (Mistborn, #3.5)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Tricky review without spoiling the book. Similarly to Bands of Mourning, I liked getting some more info on what's going on in the Cosmere, but this was too little to really help (me, at least). Perhaps with a Cliff's Notes on the Cosmere, I'd enjoy this more, but as it is, it was too much of a tease.

Title: The Bands of Mourning (Mistborn, #6)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Perhaps my favorite of the Wax/Wayne series so far, although this still hasn't reached the heights that the original Mistborn trilogy did. I like how Steris is finally growing into herself (finally, I might add), but thought the main character plot twist to be pretty obvious from the start. And while I enjoyed seeing more Scadrial "tech", I found it a bit much all at once. So, I'm pretty conflicted about this, and had to immediately buy and read Secret History once I finished.

Also, while I love the idea of the Cosmere, I wonder if the focus on a much broader scale is affecting the quality of the individual books/series set in it.

Title: The Code Book: The Science of Secrecy from Ancient Egypt to Quantum Cryptography
Author: Simon Singh
My Review:
Highly enjoyable read. It was fascinating to find out more about the history and stories of cryptography, although I wound up just skimming past the math/physics since I'd already taken those courses a long, long time ago. I especially enjoyed the details of Enigma and some of the backstories behind Diffie-Hellman and RSA.

Thanks for the recommendation, Ellen!

Title: Paper Towns
Author: John Green
My Review: Lovely read, even if it isn't my usual fare.

Title: We Were Liars
Author: E. Lockhart
My Review: 2.5/5 - I can't believe this is YA...! It's a very interesting read, although wasn't really up my alley.

Title: Divergent (Divergent, #1)
Author: Veronica Roth
My Review: Fun read, but the romance and characters were a stretch.

Title: The Summer Prince
Author: Alaya Dawn Johnson
My Review: Although I enjoyed actually reading the book, it didn't hold up quite as well on further reflection.

Title: This Side of Home
Author: Renée Watson
My Review: 3.5/5 - A really nice read that takes a look at racism and gentrification in Portland. The author doesn't get too deep or heavy into the subjects, which is understandable given the genre. One of the books I've enjoyed the most for our YA book club so far.

Title: Graceling (Graceling Realm, #1)
Author: Kristin Cashore
My Review: 4.5/5 - Favorite YA book this year so far!

Title: A Wizard of Earthsea (Earthsea Cycle, #1)
Author: Ursula K. Le Guin
My Review:
Should really be a 3.5/5. I just wasn't as impressed by this as I expected to be. It wasn't bad, and perhaps I would've liked it better had I not seen similar concepts elsewhere.

Also, I don't particularly enjoy reading about the main character traveling. (Much like with Tolkien.)

Title: Two Serpents Rise (Craft Sequence, #2)
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review: After reading the first book in this series, I actually went and bought this for the flight back home. Pretty much the same as the first book - a fantastic universe, well-plotted, and great characters. Very reminiscent of Sanderson, although with better characters and a slightly less satisfying plot resolution. (Which really isn't a knock on Gladstone; Sanderson really excels at plot resolution!)

Title: The Clockwork Rocket (Orthogonal, #1)
Author: Greg Egan
My Review: Incredibly fascinating premise, but I didn't really want to spend the time to truly grok the science behind this universe. Not sure who the target audience for this book is, but I enjoyed the concept enough to skim it.

Title: Full Fathom Five (Craft Sequence, #3)
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review: 3.5/5 - Still love the Craft Sequence universe, but I figured out most of the plot twists in this pretty quickly, so it just wasn't quite as satisfying as the previous books.

Title: City of Stairs (The Divine Cities, #1)
Author: Robert Jackson Bennett
My Review: 3.5/5 - Nothing mindblowing, but a solid and enjoyable read.

Title: The Life-Changing Magic of Tidying Up: The Japanese Art of Decluttering and Organizing
Author: Marie Kondō
My Review: Some interesting tips, but I felt like this book could've been condensed into maybe ten or so pages. I skimmed most of the book.

Title: The Eternal Flame (Orthogonal, #2)
Author: Greg Egan
My Review: Pretty much the same as the last book - a fascinating universe, but I skimmed a lot of the science-y bits. I assume the physics is solid, although I'm curious whether the biology is reasonable or not.

Title: The Arrows of Time (Orthogonal #3)
Author: Greg Egan
My Review:
Greg Egan is insane, in the best of ways. I had to skim a lot of this book, and didn't really understand a lot of the science. I would've preferred "non-fiction" books in this universe, with less plot and explanations of the science aimed at novices.

Still, I absolutely love the concept. Just need Cliff's Notes for the science or something...

Title: Just Ride: A Radically Practical Guide to Riding Your Bike
Author: Grant Petersen
My Review: 4.5/5 - Really liked the concept behind this book - the influence of racing on biking is huge, and not necessarily for the better. Given how much I agreed with the section on fitness (for the most part), I can be reasonably certain that I'd probably agree similarly for the rest of his advice.

Title: Karma
Author: Cathy Ostlere
My Review: Nice writing, but some pretty weird plot in the latter half of the book.

Title: The Phoenix Project: A Novel About IT, DevOps, and Helping Your Business Win
Author: Gene Kim
My Review: Kind of preachy and one-dimensional, but a good read nonetheless. Probably because I largely agree with the book's points. It's worth reading if you're into IT management theory, and it's an easy read too.

Title: Ancillary Sword (Imperial Radch, #2)
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review: Although I liked the first book, I wasn't sure whether I enjoyed it enough to keep reading the series. But given that I chewed through this in just a couple of days, I think it's safe to say that I'm definitely going to read the next one.

Title: The Grace of Kings (The Dandelion Dynasty, #1)
Author: Ken Liu
My Review: 3.5/5 - Written in a unique style - really reads like a tale of legend told from the distant past.

Title: The Human Division (Old Man's War, #5)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: Enjoyable, but leaves more strands hanging that resolved. The transitions between each chapter are a little rough, probably due to the episodic nature of the book.

Title: Caliban's War (The Expanse, #2)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: 3.5/5 - Quite enjoyed this one. Even more than the first book, I think.

Title: Last First Snow (Craft Sequence, #4)
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review: Another great read from Gladstone. Really enjoyed seeing familiar characters in the past, and makes me want to read Two Serpents Rise again.

Title: The Art of Smart Football
Author: Chris B. Brown
My Review: Great read. A bit of deja vu if you've been reading his work online, but still very worthwhile. Makes me look forward even more to football season kicking into gear!

Title: The Flicker Men
Author: Ted Kosmatka
My Review: Really promising start, but it went off the rails for me in the third act. It almost reads like two different books, and there just wasn't enough tie-in from the setup to the ending for me. I wish it had either explored the main scientific premise more or concentrated on the more mystery-action in the end.

Title: Seveneves
Author: Neal Stephenson
My Review: Really enjoyed Seveneves. Only knocks for me were the excessive descriptions of technology (which I mostly skimmed) and some of the worldbuilding stretched my suspension of disbelief. But overall, this is one of my favorite Stephenson reads so far.

Title: The Traitor Baru Cormorant (The Masquerade, #1)
Author: Seth Dickinson
My Review: 4.5/5 - Such an interesting book - would highly recommend for people who enjoy more political-style fantasy. Political intrigues like Game of Thrones, but more focused on government. Also reminds me a lot of Max Gladstone's work, but with more politics/economics and less magic. I have a hard time explaining this book, but it was fantastic.

Title: The End of All Things (Old Man's War, #6)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: 2.5/5 - Entertaining, but not as good as Scalzi's previous works.

Title: Cibola Burn (The Expanse, #4)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: 3.5/5 - Took a few strange turns and had some weird pacing, but I'm still interested enough in the series to read the next book.

Title: Nemesis Games (The Expanse, #5)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: A worthy continuation of the series. I liked the change of pace with the crew split up, and the returns of some familiar faces.

Title: Shadows of Self (Mistborn, #5)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Liked it, but not as much as previous works by Sanderson. Characters just felt flatter, and there wasn't as much meat to the story. The main twist was pretty predictable, and the secondary twist at the end felt pretty contrived. I wonder if this was since Bands of Mourning was written first? In any case, I'm still eagerly awaiting Bands of Mourning and hoping that everything comes together satisfactorily there.

Also, the Cosmere is starting to get pretty complicated, and I'm having trouble keeping track of all the various worlds and Shards and gods, which I especially realized when reading the appendix to Shadows of Self.

Title: The Unmapped Lands
Author: Theresa Couchman
My Review: An enjoyable read, but a little too "fantastic" (in the fantasy sense of the word) for my liking.

Title: Fables, Vol. 22: Farewell
Author: Bill Willingham
Additional Authors: Mark Buckingham, Steve Leialoha, Andrew Pepoy, Dan           Green, José Marzán Jr., David Petersen, Russ Braun, Joëlle Jones, Mark Schultz, Lee Garbett, Teddy Kristiansen, Mike Allred, Aaron Alexovich, David Hahn, Lan Medina, Niko Henrichon, Terry Dodson, Rachel Dodson, Mark Farmer, Megan Levens, Bryan Talbot, Lee Loughridge, Andrew Dalhouse, Laura Allred, Todd Klein, Nimit Malavi

Title: Abaddon's Gate (Expanse, #3)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: My favorite of the series as yet. Fast paced, and just enough about the creators of the protomolecule to pique my interest without being frustrating or taking over the rest of the plot.

Title: Fables, Vol. 20: Camelot
Author: Bill Willingham
Additional Authors: Mark Buckingham, Steve Leialoha, Russ Braun, Barry Kitson, Andrew Pepoy, Gary Erskine

Title: Flex ('Mancer, #1)
Author: Ferrett Steinmetz
My Review:
An enjoyable read. I liked it overall, although the resolution of the main plot was a bit too pat for me. Otherwise, it was fun and good enough that I'll probably read the sequel when it comes out.

I do kind of wonder if this would've been better as a YA book, though...

Title: The Long War (The Long Earth, #2)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: Interesting, but felt somewhat discombobulated. Several plot threads that didn't come together entirely naturally.

Title: Collision Low Crossers: A Year Inside the Turbulent World of NFL Football
Author: Nicholas Dawidoff
My Review: Had some interesting bits, but something about the writing just didn't work for me. I gave up on it after checking it out twice from the library.

Title: Pratchett's women: unauthorised essays on the female characters of Discworld
Author: Tansy Rayner Roberts

Title: Three Parts Dead (Craft Sequence, #1)
Author: Max Gladstone
My Review:
My kind of SF! Reminded me a lot of Sanderson, actually. A very intricate world, with all the pieces clicking into place at the end. Not quite as satisfying as Sanderson in the latter respect, but Gladstone makes up for it in other ways.

Also, the main protagonist is refreshingly female with no love interest.

Title: The Final Empire (Mistborn, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Quite enjoyed the magic system. Figured out a couple of the twists, but not the biggest one. Really looking forward to reading the next two books.

Title: Firefight (The Reckoners, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - The main character is a bit too YA-cheeky for my taste, and the plot didn't quite come together as tightly as I had hoped. Still, I have high hopes for the next book in the series (Calamity) based on some of the reveals at the end of Firefight.

Title: Hellstrom's Hive
Author: Frank Herbert
My Review: As usual, it's always neat to read Herbert's older works to see influences on Dune, but the book didn't hold up too well as a whole otherwise.

Title: The Martian
Author: Andy Weir
My Review: A great read! Everything was believable (for this non-biologist/orbital mechanic/astronomer, at any rate), and none of the mishaps/solutions felt like deus ex machinas. Highly recommended if the concept sounds interesting, and it's a pretty short read as well.

Title: Invisibles: The Power of Anonymous Work in an Age of Relentless Self-Promotion
Author: David     Zweig
My Review: Really enjoyed the individual stories, but the book was a bit too preachy about "invisibles" for me in general.

Title: Skin Deep (Legion, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Enjoyable, but felt pretty shallow in comparison to Sanderson's usual works. Regardless, I enjoyed the resolution and really want more revelations about Leeds' ability.

Title: Creativity, Inc.: Overcoming the Unseen Forces That Stand in the Way of True Inspiration
Author: Ed Catmull
My Review: 4.5/5 - Would probably have been just as good had this been just a peek behind the scenes at Pixar, but the management stuff is actually pretty interesting too.

Title: Hyperion
Author: Dan Simmons
My Review: Good read overall, but it ends on a really unsatisfying (and frustrating) cliffhanger.

Title: Echopraxia (Firefall, #2)
Author: Peter Watts
My Review: A worthy successor to Blindsight.

Title: Stuff Matters: Exploring the Marvelous Materials That Shape Our Man-Made World
Author: Mark Miodownik

Title: Lords and Ladies (Discworld, #14; Witches #4)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: For some reason, felt like going back and re-reading some of Pratchett's earlier works. This was more abrupt than I remembered, but still good stuff.

Title: Blindsight (Firefall, #1)
Author: Peter Watts
My Review:
Available to read online here: http://www.rifters.com/real/Blindsight.htm

Watts writes SF the way I like it; very hard and with an abundance of awesome ideas.

Title: Nexus (Nexus, #1)
Author: Ramez Naam
My Review: A fun read, but a little too straightforward and implausible for me. Otherwise, I enjoyed the action and general moments of awesome/cool tech in the book though.

Title: The Dragonriders of Pern (Dragonriders of Pern, #1-3)
Author: Anne McCaffrey
My Review: Not as good as when I read these in my childhood.

Title: Parasite (Parasitology, #1)
Author: Mira Grant
My Review: Not as good as Newsflesh. Kind of far-fetched, and I couldn't buy into the character motivations. Lots of coincidences, which didn't help with the believability.

Title: Restaurant Man
Author: Joe Bastianich
My Review: Entertaining read. A bit smug/self-serving, but pretty much what I expected given his actions and behavior on Masterchef.

Title: Iron Sunrise (Eschaton, #2)
Author: Charles Stross
My Review: Not as good as the first book. Entertaining enough to finish, but it was a little all over the place.

Title: Terra Insegura
Author: Edward Willett
My Review: Meh. Good enough to finish once I had started, but nothing really special about the story, characters, or world.

Title: Beginnings (Worlds of Honor, #6)
Author: David Weber
Additional Authors: Charles E. Gannon, Joelle Presby, Timothy Zahn
My Review: An enjoyable read overall, with the first story being the weak link of the bunch.

Title: The City & the City
Author: China Miéville
My Review: Pretty impressive writing to keep me engaged despite the lack of plot. I didn't realize until halfway through the book that pretty much nothing had happened. So even though this isn't my usual fare, and there was no plot for most of the book, and a kind of bizarre plot at the end, I quite enjoyed reading this.

Title: Raising Steam (Discworld, #40, Moist von Lipwig #3)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: The first Pratchett book I've read that I had to slog through. The dialogue and plot felt forced, and the characters not as charming as they used to be.

Title: Singularity Sky (Eschaton, #1)
Author: Charles Stross
My Review:
3.5/5 - I mentally had this as a 4/5 immediately after reading, but the plot didn't stand up as well once I finished the book and thought about it. Nonetheless, I really enjoyed actually reading this book (I love me spies, space opera, and singularities) even if it was a little lacking afterwards.

The plot has historical analogues, so the Wikipedia entry is interesting too: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singularity_Sky#History

Title: Words of Radiance (The Stormlight Archive, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - Glad to see more plot progression, but it just wasn't as interesting as the previous book, and the ending wasn't as intellectually satisfying as I've come to expect from Sanderson. Still, I'm eagerly awaiting the next volume.

Title: Masters of Doom: How Two Guys Created an Empire and Transformed Pop Culture
Author: David Kushner
My Review: 3.5/5 - Since I wasn't into computers and FPS for much of this timeline, this was a nice dip into history that I was previously unaware of. I wish it were more technical, but it was still a good read nonetheless.

Title: A Storm of Swords (A Song of Ice and Fire, #3)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: The Atrocity Archives (Laundry Files, #1)
Author: Charles Stross
My Review: A very fun read that crosses several genres. How could I resist a mashup of IT + Lovecraft + spy thriller?

Title: Slow Getting Up: A Story of NFL Survival from the Bottom of the Pile
Author: Nate Jackson
My Review: I quite enjoyed this behind-the-scenes look at pro football, but it's probably not that interesting for the layperson.

Title: Iron Chef: The Official Book
Author: Fuji Television
My Review: The interviews with the cast and people who worked on the show were interesting, but the rest was just fluff.

Title: Dangerous Women
Author: George R.R. Martin
Additional Authors: Gardner Dozois, Carrie Vaughn, Lev Gossman, Joe R. Lansdale, Megan Lindholm, Lawrence Block, Brandon Sanderson, Sharon Kay Penman, Lev Grossman, Nancy Kress, Diana Rowland, Diana Gabaldon, S.M. Stirling, Sam Sykes, Pat Cadigan, Caroline Spector, Joe Abercrombie, Megan Abbott, Cecelia Holland, Jim Butcher, Sherrilyn Kenyon, Melinda M. Snodgrass
My Review: I definitely enjoyed the stories by the authors I'd already read, but the ones by the writers I hadn't heard of were not as compelling for me.

Title: Beyond the Rift
Author: Peter Watts
My Review: 3.5/5 - Mixed bag of short stories, which I liked for the most part, but I prefer Watts' long-form stuff.

Title: The Devil in the White City: Murder, Magic, and Madness at the Fair That Changed America
Author: Erik Larson
My Review: An entertaining read about the World Fair in Chicago. I enjoyed reading about both storylines, although they never really synced up together very well. Also, the end of the Holmes story was rather anticlimactic. Despite these nitpicks, it was a very interesting read. I initially thought it would be 4.5 stars, but the ending brought it back down to 4.

Title: Bride of Death (Marla Mason, #7)
Author: T.A. Pratt
My Review: While I didn't like the POV at first, it grew on me and I didn't mind it as much by the end. Overall, not as exciting as previous books, perhaps since Marla is now the bride of death.

Title: The Numbers Game: Why Everything You Know About Soccer Is Wrong
Author: Chris  Anderson
My Review: Not bad, but a little more simplistic than I was looking for. Lots of interesting nuggets, but I would've preferred a deeper analysis.

Title: Ancillary Justice (Imperial Radch, #1)
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review: A very different SF book than my usual, but one that I enjoyed quite a lot anyway. (Much less pulpy and probably better written than my usual fare. Still had a great depth of universe, and also more character-driven rather than plot-driven as well.)

Title: Surface Detail (Culture #9)
Author: Iain M. Banks
My Review: Quite liked it overall, although I'm not sure how I feel about the perspective-jumping throughout, which made it a little hard to reach piecemeal.

Title: Steelheart (Reckoners, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Enjoyed the read, but simpler and pulpier than his other works. The plot twists and payoff at the end just wasn't as awesome as with Mistborn, Emperor's Soul, etc. I'm still looking forward to the next one, though.

Title: Confident Ruby
Author: Avdi Grimm
My Review: Lots of good stuff, especially for people who aren't too familiar with Ruby. If you read enough source, you'll see these patterns in the better libraries, but it's nice to have these explicitly stated and thought through.

Title: Redshirts
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun read, pretty much exactly what I was expecting.

Title: Redemption (Infinity Blade, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: A fun read, although a little insubstantial.

Title: Dust (Silo, #3)
Author: Hugh Howey
My Review: It was nice to finally see what was going on behind the scenes of Silo #1, but the story as a whole felt somewhat rushed. I enjoyed the conclusion to the series, even if I didn't like the actual story as much as in previous books.

Title: The Sports Gene: Inside the Science of Extraordinary Athletic Performance
Author: David   Epstein
My Review: 5/5 - A fantastic read for anyone who's into sports, genetics, and/or performance.

Title: This is How You Die: Stories of the Inscrutable, Infallible, Inescapable Machine of Death (Machine of Death, #2)
Author: Ryan North
Additional Authors: Matthew Bennardo, David Malki, 'Nathan Burgoine, Toby W. Rush, Rhiannon Kelly, Ryan Estrada, George Page III, Chandler Kaiden, Tom Francis, Grace Seybold, D.L.E. Roger, Daliso Chaponda, John Takis, Ada Hoffmann, Karen Stay Ahlstrom, Gord Sellar, Marleigh Norton, Sarah Pavis, Ren Warom, Liz Argall, John Chernega, Bill Chernega, Richard Salter, Ed    Turner, Hollan Lane, Martin Livings, Kyle Schoenfeld, M.J. Leitch, Brigita Orel, Erika Hammerschmidt, Rebecca    Black
My Review: For the most part, I enjoyed this more than the first book - had a greater hit-to-miss ratio.

Title: Third Shift: Pact (Shift, #3)
Author: Hugh Howey
My Review: I was glad to finally get more information behind the true purpose of the Silos, but it was a somewhat slow read overall, possibly since I wasn't that interested in Silo 1 just as exposition/for moving the plot along and Silo 17 was just about getting Solo to the point where he meets Jules in the previous books.

Title: Unfettered (Unfettered, #1)
Author: Shawn Speakman
Additional Authors: Robert Jordan, Terry Brooks, Patrick Rothfuss, Brandon Sanderson, Jacqueline Carey, Tad Williams, R.A. Salvatore, Naomi Novik, Geno Salvatore, Peter V. Brett, Daniel Abraham, Lev Grossman, David Anthony Durham, Peter Orullian, Blake Charlton, Michael J. Sullivan, Eldon Thompson, Robert V.S. Redick, Carrie Vaughn, Kevin Hearne, Jennifer Bosworth, Todd Lockwood, Mark  Lawrence
My Review: 4.5/5 - I enjoyed most of the stories in this collection quite a lot, and those that I didn't love, I still liked. Definitely worth it if you're familiar with more than a few of these authors.

Title: Tales from the White Hart
Author: Arthur C. Clarke
My Review: I tried to like it, but just couldn't get into it. I think the vignette-y nature of the tales just didn't really keep my interest.

Title: The Rithmatist (Rithmatist, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Pretty much exactly what I'd expect from a YA Sanderson book. As usual, I wish we got to see more of the underpinnings of the magic system, but I expect that sequels will dig more in that direction. Also, I really like how the main protagonist isn't a Rithmatist!

Title: The Honor of the Queen (Honor Harrington, #2)
Author: David Weber
My Review: Kind of surprised I haven't rated this before. This is a re-read since it was on sale for the Kindle. Entertaining as always, but did not hold up as well as I thought it would.

Title: Awakening (Infinity Blade, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Read this mostly because it was on sale for $0.99 and I enjoy Sanderson. A fun read, as things go, but I wish it were more than just a short story.

Title: Practical Object Oriented Design in Ruby
Author: Sandi Metz
My Review: 4.5/5 - One of the few programming books which has content that actually matches the title. Lots of very useful (practical) suggestions on writing code in Ruby, and the book avoids getting too high-level, for better or worse.

Title: Accidents in North American Mountaineering, Volume 10, Number 2, Issue 65
Author: Jed Williamson
My Review: A must-read for anyone who climbs.

Title: The Secret Race: Inside the Hidden World of the Tour de France: Doping, Cover-ups, and Winning at All Costs
Author: Tyler Hamilton
My Review: 4.5/5 - An incredibly fascinating read about doping in bicycling. Hamilton is surprisingly forthright, and doesn't try to make excuses for himself.

Title: Brainiac: Adventures in the Curious, Competitive, Compulsive World of Trivia Buffs
Author: Ken Jennings
My Review: Fun to read, although not as interesting as I thought it would be. Jennings intersperses talking about his experiences on Jeopardy with writing about trivia in general, and although the latter is neat, it's not something I'm particularly interested in.

Title: Invasion (The Secret World Chronicles, #1)
Author: Mercedes Lackey
Additional Authors: Steve Libbey, Cody Martin, Dennis Lee
My Review: Got about a third of the way through before I gave up. Read like bad fanfiction.

Title: Abhorsen (Abhorsen, #3)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review: Again, a fun read, but the plotting was a little too contrived for my taste.

Title: Lirael (Abhorsen, #2)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review: A mostly fun read (barely getting to 3 stars for me), but the cliffhanger ending was more than a little annoying. Weirdly paced, too.

Title: The Emperor's Soul
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 4.5/5 - As usual, a fantastic magic system and tight plotting. Only nitpick is that the compressed timescale and what Shai is able to accomplish in it was a bit too deus-ex-machina for me.

Title: Coaching Confidential: Inside the Fraternity of NFL Coaches
Author: Gary Myers
My Review: 2.5/5 - Mostly history, which I wasn't so interested in. Not enough anecdotes/strategy for my taste.

Title: Is Everyone Hanging Out Without Me? (And Other Concerns)
Author: Mindy Kaling
My Review: There were some pretty funny parts, but fell kind of flat overall.

Title: Second Shift: Order (Shift, #2)
Author: Hugh Howey
My Review: This just wasn't as gripping as the previous books in the series. I still have high hopes for the remaining books, though!

Title: Reamde
Author: Neal Stephenson
My Review: The story is pretty far fetched, but I rather enjoyed the book.

Title: Tmux: Productive Mouse-Free Development
Author: Brian P. Hogan
My Review: 3.5/5 - Great guide to tmux, although I was already familiar with probably the first half of the book. That being said, I still picked up a few tips from those sections, learned much about tmux's panes, and it's nice to have a comprehensive guide to using tmux for pair programming. Probably most useful to a tmux newbie, but not as useful for someone who already uses tmux's sessions and panes.

Title: Zoo City
Author: Lauren Beukes
My Review: 3.5/5 - Fun read, but some of the plot felt a bit forced. Neat concept for the world, though.

Title: Effective Programming: More Than Writing Code
Author: Jeff Atwood
My Review: 3.5/5 - I've already read most of this before, so nothing new, but kind of nice to have a "best hits" compiled into a single collection. As usual, Atwood does a nice job of hitting broad and general points, although one could quibble with some of the details.

Title: Pump Six and Other Stories
Author: Paolo Bacigalupi
My Review: 3.5/5 - Enjoyable, although as with his other works, I really just want to read more about the universe!

Title: The Hydrogen Sonata (Culture #10)
Author: Iain M. Banks
My Review: 3.5/5 - More or less a typical Culture novel. As usual, I love the universe and how Banks drops in tantalizing details about the world. And as usual, I wish there were more reveals, even though that's part of the charm of reading a Culture novel. The ending was especially non-enlightening, but it's always been about the journey, not the destination, for these books.

Title: The Heroes (First Law World, #5)
Author: Joe Abercrombie
My Review: I'm still not entirely sure how I feel about this book. I did enjoy the overall story and characters, but there was just something that wasn't quite there. Anyway, worth reading if you like the number of characters of GRRM/WoT (as well as the character deaths in GRRM), and don't overly care about the story outside of the battle (which takes place over a few days).

Title: Legion (Legion, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Nifty concept, but I really wish there were more to this story!

Title: The Heaven Makers
Author: Frank Herbert
My Review: Not as good as some of Herbert's other early works, but still interesting to see some of the themes that lead through to Dune.

Title: War Maid's Choice (War God, #4)
Author: David Weber
My Review: Pretty ho-hum. The bantering (such as it was) got on my nerves.

Title: Caine's Law (The Acts of Caine, #4)
Author: Matthew Woodring Stover
My Review: 3.5/5 - I think I need to re-read this to give it a proper rating. Thoroughly confusing, but very Stover.

Title: The Way of Kings (The Stormlight Archive, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
I don't know why I was so worried I wouldn't like this book. All the complaining about the abundance of characters was far overstated (or maybe I'm just used to it from GRRM?). There were a handful of throwaway characters, but nothing like what I was expecting from other reviews! As usual, an intriguing world, although I really wish this was less of a setup novel and revealed more of what was actually going on in terms of the series as a whole.

Basically, if you liked Sanderson's other novels, I don't see why you wouldn't like this one.

Also, this was just about the perfect length for IAD-SFO-SEA.

Title: The Perfection Point: Sport Science Predicts the Fastest Man, the Highest Jump, and the Limits of Athletic Performance
Author: John Brenkus
My Review: 3.5 stars. I found the science to be pretty suspect, especially since it's given without much explanation, but that doesn't make the book any less fun to read. Actually, it probably makes the book much more interesting to read, since I imagine any detailed explanation of why changing X would increase the distance/speed by Y% would probably be pretty boring.

Title: Torch of Freedom (Honorverse: Wages of Sin, #2)
Author: David Weber
My Review: 3.5 stars. Nice to see the background of what happened on Mesa, although the Torch series reads a bit flimsy compared to the main Honorverse books.

Title: The Games That Changed the Game: The Evolution of the NFL in Seven Sundays
Author: Ron Jaworski
Additional Authors: David Plaut, Greg Cosell, Steve Sabol
My Review: 3.5 stars. A great read for anyone who's into football strategy and/or history. Jaworski did a good job intertwining football history with personal anecdotes, and I think the book is quite readable even by people who aren't too familiar with football. One knock on the book in this respect is that going through so many drives in each game could sometimes become dull, and some of the game summaries probably would've benefited from further editing. A very enjoyable read, although I would've personally preferred it to have more X's and O's.

Title: Blackout (Newsflesh Trilogy, #3)
Author: Mira Grant
My Review: 3.5/5 - A nice way to close out the series, although I was a little disappointed with some of the revelations and the overall plot in general.

Title: Build Awesome Command-Line Applications in Ruby: Control Your Computer, Simplify Your Life
Author: David B. Copeland
My Review: 3.5/5 - Not a bad introduction to command line apps, and lots of good information sprinkled throughout, but it wasn't quite what I was expecting.

Title: Acacia: The War with the Mein (Acacia, #1)
Author: David Anthony Durham
My Review: A strange combination of epic Rule of Cool and GRRM-esque realism. The Rule of Cool wins over realism for most of the book, but I did enjoy the plot turns towards the end of the story. So... I liked the book, but there was that strange tension between the two aspects.

Title: Postsingular
Author: Rudy Rucker
My Review: 3.5/5 - An enjoyable read about the singularity. Good enough that I want to read the sequel.

Title: Everyone in Silico
Author: Jim Munroe
My Review: Neat ideas, but little followthrough.

Title: Ready Player One (Ready Player One, #1)
Author: Ernest Cline
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun read, though I found the overall premise hard to swallow. Also, I find it hard to believe that any single persons could be good enough to be /that/ good at all of these 80's games.

Title: First Shift: Legacy (Shift, #1)
Author: Hugh Howey
My Review: 3.5/5 - Neat for those who are familiar with the Wool-verse, but I could've used more plot/characters instead of just the little amount of setup for how Wool came to be.

Title: Leviathan Wakes (The Expanse, #1)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review: 3.5/5 - Started off a bit slow, but I'm glad I stuck with it. Mostly space opera, but with a splash of noir and zombies that didn't overwhelm. I enjoyed the dichotomy between the main characters, and the mostly-believable physics was nice as well.

Title: The Cure for Everything: Untangling Twisted Messages about Health, Fitness, and Happiness
Author: Timothy Caulfield
My Review: 3.5/5 - A good read for anyone interested in health, although a little boring for me since I didn't learn anything new. Basically eat smart, exercise for health and not weight, and pseudoscience is pseudoscience.

Title: I Am Maru
Author: Mugumogu
My Review: 3.5/5 - Who knew there was a book about Maru? I saw this at the library and picked it up. It's pretty much exactly what you'd expect.

Title: Smalltalk Best Practice Patterns
Author: Kent Beck
My Review: 4.5/5 - Not many people use Smalltalk, but this is a pretty great read for Ruby and Objective-C, as both languages inherit much of Smalltalk's base concepts. A lot of the patterns are obvious (some in general, some in hindsight), but it's nice to have them actually explained and put down into words.

Title: Exceptional Ruby: Master the Art of Handling Failure in Ruby
Author: Avdi Grimm
My Review: A nice, succinct read on exception handling in Ruby. I learned some good stuff here, especially guidance on when exceptions should be used.

Title: A Rising Thunder (Honor Harrington, #13)
Author: David Weber
My Review: 3.5/5 - This was a surprisingly short HH book! I've gotten used to the weighty tomes that were the previous few books in the series. While it was enjoyable, not much actually happened and this felt like it was just setting the stage for the next book in the series (for which I am anxiously awaiting).

Title: Wool Omnibus (Silo, #1)
Author: Hugh Howey
My Review: 4.5/5 - Pretty fantastic stuff. Howey starts off with a great short story in Wool #1 (and could easily have ended there), but I'm glad he didn't.

Title: One Jump Ahead:: Challenging Human Supremacy in Checkers
Author: Jonathan Schaeffer
My Review: 4.5/5 - If you liked Behind Deep Blue or the Maven thesis, this will be right up your alley. A wonderful history on the progression of Chinook as a checkers AI on through the solving of checkers. Highly recommended for anyone who enjoys reading about computer game AI.

Title: Downbelow Station (The Company Wars, #1)
Author: C.J. Cherryh
My Review: A pretty satisfying ending to a kind of boring rest of the book.

Title: Broken Angels (Takeshi Kovacs, #2)
Author: Richard K. Morgan
My Review: 3.5/5 - Good enough that I had a hard time putting it down, but the characters and ending were somewhat underwhelming. Still merits the rating due to the action/plot and universe.

Title: Into Thin Air: A Personal Account of the Mount Everest Disaster
Author: Jon Krakauer
My Review: A first person recollection of what happened in the Everest disaster of 1996. I found this pretty interesting, as I've never done any mountaineering before.

Title: A Dance with Dragons (A Song of Ice and Fire, #5)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: The Alloy of Law (Mistborn, #4)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Pretty fantastic continuation to the initial Mistborn trilogy. Some random thoughts about the book:

* Love that a new allomatic power was introduced by page 50.
* The time gap between the previous series and this book strongly reminded me of both Dune (God Emperor) and Avatar (Legend of Korra); the former because of the past becoming myth, and the latter due to the move towards an industrial setting from a medieval one.
* As usual, Sanderson has some of the tightest plotting in SFF I've read in a long time. Also some of the most satisfying solutions to mysteries. (Just as with the previous books, I figured some of them out while reading, and the reveals which I did not figure out were fantastic.)

Title: Which Comes First, Cardio or Weights?: Fitness Myths, Training Truths, and Other Surprising Discoveries from the Science of Exercise
Author: Alex  Hutchinson
My Review: Pretty useful book that summarizes a lot of the current knowledge behind exercise. I especially liked that the author isn't afraid to come out and say when the science is inconclusive.

Title: Snuff (Discworld, #39; City Watch #8)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: Vimes is my favorite Discworld character, so this rating was probably a foregone conclusion. The Ankh-Morpork plotline felt a little weak though, and I thought the killer-going-after-Vimes was a bit too reminiscent of what happened in Thud!.

Title: The Children of the Sky  (Zones of Thought, #3)
Author: Vernor Vinge
My Review: 3.5/5 - I liked it, but really, I want more of the Beyond and not the Down Here.

Title: Andy Roddick Beat Me with a Frying Pan: Taking the Field with Pro Athletes and Olympic Legends to Answer Sports Fans' Burning Questions
Author: Todd Gallagher
My Review: I really liked this, but it combines sports and random hypotheticals, so how could I not?

Title: Die Trying (Jack Reacher, #2)
Author: Lee Child
My Review: 3.5/5 - It's rather refreshing to have main characters actually be competent, although Reacher and Holly might be a bit too much so... still, I like it.

Title: Running Blind (Jack Reacher, #4)
Author: Lee Child
My Review: I was underwhelmed by the reveal.

Title: Zoe's Tale (Old Man's War, #4)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review:
I had this eerie sense of deja vu while reading through the book. I vaguely knew what was going on, although couldn't put my finger on exactly what would happen.
