Embarrassingly enough, it wasn't until the author's note that I realized this took place alongside Last Colony, but from a different viewpoint.

The rating should really be 3.5/5. I enjoyed reading it, but really, it just makes me want to reread Last Colony again.

Title: MetaGame
Author: Sam Landstrom
My Review: I quite enjoyed this. Loved the setting, even though the end seemed a bit rushed.

Title: Countdown (Newsflesh Trilogy, #0.25)
Author: Mira Grant
My Review: 2.5/5. Coming from the point of view of someone who's already read the first two books, the content was not terribly interesting for me.

Title: Practical Programming for Strength Training
Author: Mark Rippetoe
My Review: Very informative - not sure I really needed all the detail, but I'm glad I have a reference if I ever want to look it up. I think Starting Strength is the book I was actually looking for, although Practical Programming was still a good read to get some more background on the theory.

Title: We Few (Empire of Man, #4)
Author: David Weber
My Review: A nice close to the Empire of Man series, while leaving enough open threads for later continuation.

Title: Killing Floor (Jack Reacher, #1)
Author: Lee Child
My Review: 2.5/3. Entertaining, but the plot was a little thin. Not nearly as good as the other Reacher novel I read, but I supposed that's to be expected, given that this is the first one in the series.

Title: Matter (Culture, #8)
Author: Iain M. Banks
My Review: As fascinating as I find the concept of the Culture, I just don't really enjoy the stories all that much. I think this will be the last Culture book I'm going to read.

Title: Hanging By A Thread: The Missions of a Helicopter Rescue Doctor
Author: Emmanuel Cauchy
My Review: I enjoyed this, although I wonder how interesting it would be for people who don't know much about mountaineering. As it was, I just barely understood most of what was going on...

Title: Elantris (Elantris, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: I thought the plotting was not nearly as good as Sanderson's other books. The magic system didn't feel as "real" as in Warbreaker or Mistborn, and seemed too deus ex machina.

Title: Consider Phlebas (Culture, #1)
Author: Iain M. Banks
My Review: Kind of neat, but was pretty flat for me.

Title: The Hero of Ages (Mistborn, #3)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Wow, what a way to tie everything together. I was quite delighted by the self-consistency with the previous books, and how neatly everything was explained. Definitely one of Sanderson's stronger points, and why I blazed through the Mistborn trilogy after reading Warbreaker.

Title: Freedom™ (Daemon, #2)
Author: Daniel Suarez
My Review: An enjoyable read, albeit fairly pulpy. Also had a strong dose of nerdy wish-fulfillment.

Title: The Well of Ascension (Mistborn, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 3.5/5 - I thought it wasn't as good as the first book, and I thought some of the twists/mysteries didn't have enough clues. However, there were some great action sequences, and I'm looking forward to the (hopeful) payoff in the third book.

Title: JavaScript: The Good Parts
Author: Douglas Crockford
My Review: This was more of a reference rather than what I had been looking for, but was full of good content about what to avoid in Javascript nonetheless.

Title: Out of the Dark (Out of the Dark, #1)
Author: David Weber
My Review: This was going to be a 3/5, but the end was a total WTF twist that came out of nowhere. Otherwise, it was pulpy and enjoyable.

Title: Warbreaker (Warbreaker, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: 4.5/5 - Wow, I really enjoyed this book. Loved the magc system, as well as the plot and the characters.

Title: Feed (Newsflesh Trilogy, #1)
Author: Mira Grant
My Review: 4.5/5 - Best zombie book I've read since World War Z. Better in a lot of ways, actually.

Title: Deadline (Newsflesh Trilogy, #2)
Author: Mira Grant
My Review: 3.5/5 - Not as good as the first book, but I'm anxiously awaiting the third.

Title: The Algebraist
Author: Iain M. Banks
My Review: The best part about this book was definitely the Dwellers.

Title: A Feast for Crows (A Song of Ice and Fire, #4)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: A Clash of Kings  (A Song of Ice and Fire, #2)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: A Game of Thrones (A Song of Ice and Fire, #1)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: The Jesus Incident (The Pandora Sequence, #1)
Author: Frank Herbert
My Review: Overall, this was interesting, but after finishing it, I have no clue what the heck just happened.

Title: Cooking for Geeks: Real Science, Great Hacks, and Good Food
Author: Jeff Potter
My Review: This probably would've been more interesting if I were more of a cooking novice. The best parts of this book for me were the interviews and the more technical/scientific explanations, although I still prefer Alton Brown's more down-to-earth style.

Title: The Wise Man's Fear (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #2)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review: 3.5 stars. Still engrossing, but I really wished we got deeper into the current storyline.

Title: The God Engines
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: I liked the concept, but the book was frustratingly short and didn't go into nearly as much depth into the universe as I would have liked.

Title: I Shall Wear Midnight (Discworld, #38; Tiffany Aching, #4)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: Overall, a pleasing read. At the end though, it felt somewhat rushed.

Title: The Games That Changed the Game: The Evolution of the NFL in Seven Sundays
Author: Ron Jaworski
Additional Authors: David Plaut, Greg Cosell, Steve Sabol

Title: Chew: The Omnivore Edition, Vol. 1
Author: John Layman
My Review: 4.5 stars. I'm really digging the comic as a whole - the universe is awesome, the story drew me in, and the art is fantastic.

Title: Let My People Go Surfing: The Education of a Reluctant Businessman
Author: Yvon Chouinard

Title: Leviathan (Leviathan, #1)
Author: Scott Westerfeld
Publisher: Simon  Schuster Books for Young Readers
My Review: 3.5 stars. Fun read. I can't resist steampunk + bioengineering.

Title: Mockingjay (The Hunger Games, #3)
Author: Suzanne Collins
My Review: 4.5 stars. Some of the story and characters were pretty contrived, but this ended pretty much exactly like I wanted it to.

Title: Avatar The Last Airbender: The Art of the Animated Series
Author: Michael Dante DiMartino

Title: An Edge in the Kitchen: The Ultimate Guide to Kitchen Knives
Author: Chad Ward
My Review:
An excellent reference for kitchen knives.

Which reminds me, I really should get my knife sharpened.

Title: The Blind Side: Evolution of a Game
Author: Michael   Lewis

Title: CryoBurn (Vorkosigan Saga, #14)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review: 3.5 stars. An enjoyable Miles adventure, although strangely shorter than I expected.

Title: Miles, Mutants, and Microbes (Vorkosigan Omnibus, #5)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review: 3.5 stars.

Title: The Walking Dead, Book One
Author: Robert Kirkman
Additional Authors: Tony Moore, Charlie Adlard, Cliff Rathburn
My Review: Saw this at the library and borrowed it (sorry, Russ!). Really good stuff, although the realism can get incredibly creepy. It's one of those stories where you just know the main characters are going to get /fucked/.

Title: Grand Central Arena  (Grand Central Arena, #1)
Author: Ryk E. Spoor
My Review: A pulpy, fun read. Really wish more of the bigger questions were answered, though. Was also hoping that humanity had evolved to be 'lucky', like Teela Brown in the Ringworld series.

Title: Peeps (Peeps, #1)
Author: Scott Westerfeld
My Review:
3.5 stars. It was pretty strange to read "Peeps" and have the term /not/ refer to citizens of the People's Republic of Haven. Also, I think of all the parasitic anecdotes/datadumps, I had already known about all but one or two. Not sure what those two things say about me...

For another look at a biological explanation for vampirism[1], check out Peter Watts' Blindsight[2]

[1] http://www.rifters.com/blindsight/vampires.htm
[2] http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48484.Blindsight

Title: Machine of Death: A Collection of Stories About People Who Know How They Will Die (Machine of Death, #1)
Author: Ryan North
Additional Authors: Matthew Bennardo, David Malki, Camille Alexa, Yahtzee Croshaw, Randall Munroe, Brian Quinlan, Jeffrey Brown, Aaron Diaz, Kazu Kibuishi, Scott C., Roger Langridge, Karl Kerschl, Cameron Stewart, Tom Francis, Dean Trippe, Erin McKean, James L. Sutter, Kate Beaton, Jeff Stautz, J. Jack Unrau, Brandon Bolt, Shannon Wheeler, Kit Yona, Vera Brosgol, Jeffrey C. Wells, Christopher Hastings, K.M. Lawrence, David Michael Wharton, Brian McLachlan, John Chernega, Paul Horn, Camron Miller, Chris Cox, Les McClaine, Kevin McShane, Kean Soo, K. Sekelsky, James Foreman, Douglas J. Lane
My Review: The anthology starts relatively slow, but the stories quickly get more interesting. This turned out to be a far better read than I had anticipated.

Title: The Wee Free Men (Discworld, #30; Tiffany Aching, #1)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: 4.5 stars. There's just something awesome about the Nac Mac Feegle and the way they talk...

Title: Shooting in the Wild: An Insider's Account of Making Movies in the Animal Kingdom
Author: Chris Palmer
My Review: 3.5 stars. This felt like it really could have been much shorter. The self-referential nature made it seem like a paper, but it covers wildlife filmography in a a manner that i had never looked at before. Definitely worth reading if you like wildlife filmography at all.

Title: Inverting the Pyramid: The History of Football Tactics
Author: Jonathan  Wilson
My Review: I was hoping for a nice introduction to soccer tactics and strategy, but this overwhelmed me with dates, names, and jargon that I was unfamiliar with. I suspect that this book would be more palatable for someone who already knows about soccer strategy, and is looking for a historical retrospective on the different soccer formations. (If this had been about American football, I probably would've been happy with the level of detail.)

Title: Crown of Slaves (Honorverse: Wages of Sin, #1)
Author: David Weber
My Review: This required a little more suspension of disbelief compared to the usual Honorverse books, but it's well worth it. It was nice to get the story of events that occurred in the "past" (for me, since I read this after reading all the way through to At All Costs in the main Honorverse series).

Title: The Service of the Sword (Worlds of Honor, #4)
Author: David Weber
Additional Authors: John Ringo, Eric Flint, Jane Lindskold, Timothy Zahn, Victor  Mitchell
My Review: 3.5 stars. This was by far my favorite of the Honorverse anthologies.

Title: Worlds of Honor (Worlds of Honor, #2)
Author: David Weber
Additional Authors: Linda Evans, Jane Lindskold, Roland J. Green
My Review: 3.5/5 - As with the other anthologies, they're fun reads, but I'm not sure short stories are the best medium for Honorverse tales.

Title: More Than Honor (Worlds of Honor, #1)
Author: David Weber
My Review: 3/5 - I liked getting the backstory for how Stephanie Harrington discovered the treecats, as well as what McQueen did to stop the Levelers. All the stories were fun, but I was pretty disappointed with the ending of the second one, which really didn't make any sense and came out of nowhere. Although if nothing else, this is worth it for the technical appendix at the end!

Title: Catching Fire (The Hunger Games, #2)
Author: Suzanne Collins
My Review: 3.5/5 - A fun read, but not nearly as good as Hunger Games. It was pretty obvious what was going on from the get-go, and the whole plot was a bit thin. Still, enjoyable to read, even if it does end on a ridiculous cliffhanger.

Title: Changer of Worlds (Worlds of Honor, #3)
Author: David Weber
My Review: 3.5/5 - I enjoyed this far more than the first two anthologies. It's really nifty to get the stories behind events that are just background in the other books, but it also seems just a bit too... neat. In any case, it's still good, and a must-read for Honorverse fans.

Title: The Hunger Games (The Hunger Games, #1)
Author: Suzanne Collins
My Review: This was much more interesting and entertaining than I thought. The world is interesting, and Collins does a good job not beating you over the head with infodumps. I'm looking forward to reading the sequels.

Title: Delivering Happiness: A Path to Profits, Passion, and Purpose
Author: Tony Hsieh
My Review:
4.5/5 - I always enjoy reading books about more ideal ways to run companies, and I do like Zappos' emphasis on culture. The cynic in me wonders if Zappos really lives up to its reputation, though.

Reminds me a lot of Maverick and Let My People Go Surfing.

Title: The Color of Magic (Discworld, #1; Rincewind, #1)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: 3.5/5 - Figured I should get around to reading the original Discworld books. A fun romp, but not nearly as good as his later works in the Discworld series.

Title: Camouflage
Author: Joe Haldeman
My Review: 3.5/5 - I enjoyed Haldeman's portrayal of aliens, and in general, the plot and characters flowed smoothly. The 'twist' was pretty obvious, and the end abrupt, but I still liked the book nonetheless.

Title: Contact with Chaos (Freehold: Grainne War, #3, Freehold, #4)
Author: Michael Z. Williamson
My Review: 2.5/5 Pretty ho-hum overall. The standard for a "first contact" book (in my opinion) is A Mote in God's Eye, which is admittedly a pretty high bar to meet. Contact with Chaos was refreshing in its realism, with only the characters' being too rational for me to wholly believe. I could have overlooked the lack of conflict, if the alien species were more interesting.

Title: Mission of Honor (Honor Harrington, #12)
Author: David Weber
My Review: 4.5/5 - All the painstaking political intrigue over the latter half of the series finally comes to a head. There's relatively little military action, but it was extremely satisfying to finally get the dirt behind the Mesan Alignment and their sneaky ways. The book ends on a spectacular political high note (which was a nice change from the usual definitive battle).

Title: Women on High: Pioneers of Mountaineering
Author: Rebecca A. Brown
My Review: 3.5/5 - The author does a great job presenting each woman as a distinct figure, which was a nice change of pace after reading Inverting the Pyramid. I could've done without the fictional accounts before each chapter, though; they seemed unnecessary.

Title: No Dribbling the Squid: Octopush, Shin Kicking, Elephant Polo, and Other Oddball Sports
Author: Michael J. Rosen
My Review: A shallow read that glosses over a bunch of random sports. A fun read, but don't expect much.

Title: Talking Hands: What Sign Language Reveals About the Mind
Author: Margalit Fox

Title: iPhone App Development: The Missing Manual
Author: Craig Hockenberry
My Review: 3.5/5 - Skimmed through the book; a solid introduction to iPhone programming, but I wish it went into a little more depth.

Title: Saturn's Children (Freyaverse #1)
Author: Charles Stross
My Review: Pulpy SF. It moved along fast enough to keep me at least moderately interested, but in the end, just wasn't all that filling.

Title: Secret Identities: The Asian American Superhero Anthology
Author: Jeff Yang
Additional Authors: Keith Chow, Parry Shen, Jerry Ma, Vince Sunico, Jamie Ford, Glenn Urieta, A.L. Baroza, Greg Pak, Sonny Liew, Michael Kang, Erwin Haya, Chi-Yun Lau, Alexander Shen, Greg LaRocoue, Naeem Mohaiemen, Tanuj Chopra, Kripa Joshi, Lynn Chen, Paul Wei, Jimmy Aquino, Keiki Agena, Ming Doyle, Hellen Jo, Jef Castro, Benton Jew, Tak Toyoshima, Alexander Tarampi, Joanthan Tsuei, Daniel Jai Lee
My Review: A few decent comics in here, but mostly full of meh web-comic-esque art. However, reading this made me realize that the only asian superhero that immediately came to mind for me was Amadeus Cho...

Title: Time Spike
Author: Eric Flint
My Review: A fun read. Trashy SF in a similar vein as Flint's 163x series. There's nothing spectacular about the book, but it hit the spot.

Title: The Currents of Space (Galactic Empire, #2)
Author: Isaac Asimov
My Review: Lucky that I spotted this at the library; I thought I'd read pretty much all of Asimov's main novels, but apparently not!

Title: Kushiel's Dart (Phèdre's Trilogy, #1)
Author: Jacqueline Carey
My Review: Political intrigue + sex in a pretty nifty world. For some reason, it's a book I highly enjoy reading, and one of the few that I've read multiple times. Yes, it's trashy, and the prose is nothing to write home about, but it's just quite readable, for a reason that I can't quite put my finger on.

Title: Rainbows End
Author: Vernor Vinge
My Review: 3.5/5 - I quite enjoyed the read. Not as magnificent as his other books, but thoroughly entertaining nonetheless.

Title: Apartment Therapy: The Eight-Step Home Cure
Author: Maxwell Gillingham-Ryan
My Review: Kind of "woo" at times with hints of New Age nonsense, but not overly so. Regardless, the book includes enough actual content to make it useful. The pacing is nice, and the author goes into just the right amount of depth to make his advice actually useful. I'm not sure how much of it I'll heed, but the information is presented in nice nuggets that make it easy to pick and choose what to implement.

Title: Momofuku
Author: David Chang
My Review: The recipes in Momofuku run the gamut from simple to absurd, but I did see a few that I want to try in the future. I also liked that this wasn't just a list of recipes, but included the history of Chang's restaurants and his thoughts on the dishes.

Title: Catch Them Being Good: Everything You Need to Know to Successfully Coach Girls
Author: Tony DiCicco
My Review: 3.5/5 - Good read, although not entirely what I was looking for. Aimed more at a higher level than what I'm coaching, but it was an interesting read nonetheless.

Title: Sports from Hell: My Search for the World's Dumbest Competition
Author: Rick Reilly
My Review: 3.5/5 - A hilarious read. I have to admit that my own sports (rock climbing and ultimate) are pretty stupid, so how could I not love other stupid sports? Highlights include having a chapter on baseball, which cracked me up, as well as another chapter on sports in New Zealand in general! This book doesn't pretend to be anything it's not, and does a great job hitting its target. In the end, I have to agree with the author - it's a pretty fantastic thing to see someone be passionate about something they love, even if it is pretty stupid to the rest of the world.

Title: The Agony of Victory: When Winning Isn't Enough
Author: Steve  Friedman
My Review: 3/5 - A nice collection of essays that seemed only tangentially related.

Title: Rework
Author: Jason Fried
My Review: 3.5/5 - Not sure I agree 100% with everything in the book, but I quite liked the presentation and did generally agree with much of it. Recommended for anyone who's interested in business and/or management, if for no other reason than to get an alternate viewpoint. (Very similar to Maverick, actually, which is another terrific book on not bending to popular opinion in business.)

Title: This Is Your Country on Drugs: The Secret History of Getting High in America
Author: Ryan Grim
My Review: 3.5/5 - Pretty interesting. The data is a bit overwhelming at times, but the author does a pretty good job making it work with each chapter. It's a nice overview of drugs in America as a whole, going into the past as well as current politics. I learned quite a few new things from the book, and it's a nice read for anyone interested in the topic.

Title: Maverick: The Success Story Behind the World's Most Unusual Workplace
Author: Ricardo Semler
My Review:
4.5/5 - Written by the CEO of a company that strives to be run as a capitalist democracy. Incredibly interesting to see Semco change from a traditional company to what it is today.

I found this to be a great read, and love the ideas that Semler espouses about running a company.

Title: The Checklist Manifesto: How to Get Things Right
Author: Atul Gawande
My Review: 4/5 - A very nice read on how checklists are a wonderful thing. I liked how the book was not overly long; Gawande goes over checklists in just the right depth for me. I especially appreciated the sections on how to implement checklists, and why they can fail to work.

Title: Exodus: The Ark
Author: Paul Chafe
My Review: 2.5/5 - Interesting enough for me to finish the book, but I wouldn't recommend it. The world and concept isn't new, but I was hoping for a good spin on the topic that just wasn't there. The plot and characters were average, and the book was overall a little disappointing.

Title: Cocoa Programming for Mac OS X
Author: Aaron Hillegass
My Review: 4.5/5 - A terrific introduction to Cocoa and Objective-C. One of the few programming books which successfully caters to experienced programmers that are new to a specific field. Hillegass dives right into the subject matter, and the book does an especially good job with pacing the examples with infodumps.

Title: The Zombie Combat Manual: A Guide to Fighting the Living Dead
Author: Roger Ma
My Review: 3.5/5 - An enjoyable read. Short and to the point.

Title: The End of Overeating: Taking Control of the Insatiable American Appetite
Author: David A. Kessler
My Review: 3.5/5 - Not as good as Mindless Eating, although I did like how each chapter was short and succinct. Gleaned some more information, but overall, just felt kind of lacking.

Title: The Greatest Show on Earth: The Evidence for Evolution
Author: Richard Dawkins
My Review: 4.5/5 - Even though I'm somewhat familiar with most of the material in this book, Dawkins does a masterful job presenting the facts behind evolution. A must-read for anyone interested in the topic.

Title: Pawn of Prophecy (The Belgariad, #1)
Author: David Eddings
My Review: 2.5/5 - Not as compelling a read as I had been led to expect. Not much actually happens, and the entire book feels more like a prologue than anything else. Still, I did like how Garion actually does the smart thing and tells people about the weird shit that's going on. And although the whiny teenager bit is probably fairly accurate, it doesn't get any less annoying as the book goes on. Overall, I'll withhold further judgment until I read the rest of the series.

Title: The Drunkard's Walk: How Randomness Rules Our Lives
Author: Leonard Mlodinow
My Review: 3.5/5 - Highly enjoyable.  Mlodinow keeps a good pace and presents information at just the right level to keep me reading even though I've previously read books on this topic. Definitely recommended for those unfamiliar with randomness, but I don't think I learned anything truly new from this book.

Title: Spell Games (Marla Mason, #4)
Author: T.A. Pratt
My Review: Overall, the story itself didn't grab me as much as in the previous books, but the events in the book sure did! I'm looking forward to the next book, which is currently being released chapter by chapter online.

Title: Mathletics: How Gamblers, Managers, and Sports Enthusiasts Use Mathematics in Baseball, Basketball, and Football
Author: Wayne L. Winston
My Review:
Overall, pretty good. A nice introduction to statistics in sports, this book did a fantastic job at keeping the content at an approachable level for a newcomer to the field. I personally wasn't as interested in the process and was hoping for a more in-depth look at the field, but I'd highly recommend this book to someone who hasn't heard of Sabermetrics or Bill James or is interested in starting their own statistical analysis of sports data.

3.5/5

Title: Magic for Beginners
Author: Kelly Link
My Review: Managed to get through 2/3rds of this book, but the short stories really didn't do it for me. I just didn't "get" it, I suppose?

Title: The Adobe Photoshop Lightroom Book for Digital Photographers
Author: Scott Kelby

Title: Cute, Quaint, Hungry And Romantic: The Aesthetics Of Consumerism
Author: Daniel       Harris
My Review:
I gave up on reading this book. Not something I easily do, but the verbiage in this book leaned towards the absurd. Here's an example:

"In the eyes of most people, whose conditioned responses to this most rigid of styles prevent them from recognizing its artificiality, things like calendars with droopy-eyed puppies pleading for attention or greeting cards with kitty cats in raincoats are the very embodiment of innocence and as such represent an absence of the designed and manipulated qualities of what is in fact a heavily mannered aesthetic."

Pretty much the entire book is written in this fashion. I really liked the ideas, but just couldn't get myself to actually read the book.

Title: Anonyponymous: The Forgotten People Behind Everyday Words
Author: John Bemelmans Marciano
My Review: An interesting concept, but kind of hard to read straight through. There's not much flow, since the book is done dictionary/encyclopedia-style.

Title: Logicomix: An Epic Search for Truth
Author: Apostolos Doxiadis
Additional Authors: Christos H. Papadimitriou, Alecos Papadatos, Annie Di Donna
My Review: Interesting, but it wasn't what I had expected/hoped.

Title: Ultimate Techniques & Tactics
Author: James Parinella
My Review: I don't think there's too much here for people who have been playing a while, but it's worth reading anyway to get a more codified version of what you learn through trial and error through playing.

Title: The Ghost Map: The Story of London's Most Terrifying Epidemic—and How It Changed Science, Cities, and the Modern World
Author: Steven Johnson

Title: Born to Run: A Hidden Tribe, Superathletes, and the Greatest Race the World Has Never Seen
Author: Christopher McDougall
My Review: What a fantastic book. An inspirational way to start off the new year. Makes me want to go running more often. I just love people who are truly passionate about something and the eccentricity that naturally comes with it.

Title: The Knight (The Wizard Knight #1)
Author: Gene Wolfe
My Review: I gave up on this book.

Title: As They See 'Em: A Fan's Travels in the Land of Umpires
Author: Bruce Weber
My Review: Would probably be more interesting if I knew/cared more about baseball. I read it mostly to gain some insight into ultimate, as it's self-reffed, but this was more stories/history about umpiring than information about the craft.

Title: Unseen Academicals (Discworld, #37; Rincewind #8)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: It's exactly what I expected. Lots of fun, although less quotable than usual and with a less spectacular denouement than I expected. I think I shall have to reread this later.

Title: Blood Engines (Marla Mason, #1)
Author: T.A. Pratt
My Review: A fun read... not deep, but thoroughly enjoyable. Marla is indeed a badass sorcerer, and damned fun to read about.

Title: The French Laundry Cookbook
Author: Thomas Keller
My Review: The recipes are crazy, but the anecdotes are interesting.

Title: 7th Son:  Descent (7th Son, #1)
Author: J.C. Hutchins
My Review:
Meh. I found the premise, characters, and plot to be thin. The hacker clone was absurd, between his internet cult and ridiculous portrayal of hacking/security. I was willing to buy into the cloning/memory tech, but my suspension of disbelief only goes so far.

Also, really, it just so happens that the 7 clones somehow wind up with different names? How convenient!

I might have overlooked all this, but the denouement was lackluster. The twist at the end (if you can call it that) was boring, and we never discover the main clone's motivation.

Title: Coders at Work: Reflections on the Craft of Programming
Author: Peter Seibel
My Review: A really enjoyable read. Not much in the way of technical details or usable advice, but an interesting look into the minds of top programmers. Very cool to see what they think, and humbling to see what they've done in their careers.

Title: Little Brother (Little Brother, #1)
Author: Cory Doctorow
My Review:
A very peculiar read. The "realness" of the subject matter chilled me to the bone while the infodumps kept me from being fully immersed in the book. (As necessary as they were, I don't need to be taught public-key cryptography, etc.) I think that characterizations were a bit of a stretch, but they weren't implausible; you can see some of the characters in real life just by turning to Fox.

Could something like this happen? It's entirely possible. Am I willing to put my comfortable life on the line to fight something like this? I don't know. If you're interested at all in personal freedoms in our current political climate, it's definitely worth reading.

Title: The Adobe Photoshop Lightroom 2 Book for Digital Photographers
Author: Scott Kelby

Title: A Deepness in the Sky (Zones of Thought, #2)
Author: Vernor Vinge

Title: Hyperspace: A Scientific Odyssey Through Parallel Universes, Time Warps, and the Tenth Dimension
Author: Michio Kaku
My Review: One of the books that really made me who I am today. I've owned several copies of Hyperspace, but keep losing them after loaning them out.

Title: The Windup Girl
Author: Paolo Bacigalupi
My Review: An okay read. The world seems fascinating, so perhaps one of the earlier novels would be more to my liking. Nice characterization, but the separate threads weren't linked enough to make the plot really cohesive.

Title: The Catch: One Play, Two Dynasties, and the Game That Changed the NFL
Author: Gary Myers
My Review: 3.5/5 - Enjoyed reading about football history; since I only recently became interested in football, I didn't know a lot of the material covered in the book. That being said, it was pretty light and fluffy.

Title: Bone Shop (Marla Mason, Prequel #1)
Author: T.A. Pratt
My Review:
Read for free here: http://www.marlamason.net/boneshop/

3.5/5 - I quite liked the world setup, and it's interesting enough to make me put the rest of the series on my to-read list.

Title: Bears Discover Fire and Other Stories
Author: Terry Bisson
My Review: 3.5/5 - an enjoyable read.

Title: Wastelands: Stories of the Apocalypse (Wastelands #1)
Author: John Joseph Adams
Additional Authors: Cory Doctorow, George R.R. Martin, Carol Emshwiller, Jonathan Lethem, Octavia E. Butler, Stephen King, Gene Wolfe, Orson Scott Card, Paolo Bacigalupi, M. Rickert
My Review: Kind of a downer to read, and the stories were pretty hit-or-miss for me.

Title: Sustainable Energy - Without the Hot Air
Author: David J.C. MacKay
My Review:
4.5/5

Fantastic book. MacKay does a good job keeping the book at an appropriate level; enough details to give us a good summary, but not so in-depth as to make it confusing. The production values are amazing, with great design in general, from the graphs to the layout. Really loved the design.

I liked that he focuses on sustainable energy and whether it's even possible, rather than digressing into a discussion on global warming.

Title: Hard Facts, Dangerous Half-Truths, and Total Nonsense: Profiting from Evidence-based Management
Author: Jeffrey Pfeffer

Title: What We Eat When We Eat Alone: Stories and 100 Recipes
Author: Deborah Madison
My Review: A light, short, and fluffy read, but quite enjoyable. I didn't bother reading the recipes, but I liked the brief look into the eating habits of strangers.

Title: Across Realtime
Author: Vernor Vinge
My Review: Not his best, but still a damned fine read. A little fluffier than I expected, but some great ideas in the second book.

Title: The Soul of a Chef: The Journey Toward Perfection
Author: Michael Ruhlman
My Review: A good read. Ruhlman covers the Master Chef Certification, which is pretty fascinating, and then goes in depth with Michael Symon and Thomas Keller.

Title: The Sunless Countries (Virga, #4)
Author: Karl Schroeder
My Review: Not as good as the previous books. Too light, without enough SF. Also, Peter Watts explored the end concept in way more depth in Blindsight.

Title: The Magicians (The Magicians, #1)
Author: Lev Grossman
My Review: Enjoyable, but thought the ending was lacking. Also, I wish the author did a better job of tying threads together. Loved the first half of the book way more than the second half, which felt rushed.

Title: Alinea
Author: Grant Achatz
My Review: Okay, so I didn't read every single recipe. It was fascinating reading the intro essays and skimming the recipes. Makes me want to eat here someday.

Title: The Immortal Iron Fist, Volume 3: The Book of the Iron Fist
Author: Matt Fraction
Additional Authors: Roy Thomas, Travel Foreman, Ed Brubaker, Leandro Fernández, Khari Evans, Mitch Breitweiser, Russ Heath, Lewis LaRosa
My Review: Same as Volume 2.

Title: The Immortal Iron Fist, Volume 2: The Seven Capital Cities of Heaven
Author: Ed Brubaker
Additional Authors: Matt Fraction, David Aja, Howard Chaykin, Dan Brereton, Jelena Kevic-Djurdjevic
My Review: Love the art and flavor/atmosphere, as well as the fighting, but the story just doesn't match up.

Title: Summer Knight (The Dresden Files, #4)
Author: Jim Butcher
My Review: 3.5/5 - similar to the last book, enjoyable (and easy) reading, but the plot was a bit too convenient.

Title: Grave Peril (The Dresden Files, #3)
Author: Jim Butcher
My Review: Not as good as the previous books. I found Dresden to jump to conclusions a bit too quickly, and also figured out the twist way too quickly.

Title: Ultramarathon Man: Confessions of an All-Night Runner
Author: Dean Karnazes
My Review: 3.5/5 - A pretty light read, not much "meat". Still, it was interesting to take a look into the mind of someone who does ultramarathons. I appreciated the author's forthrightness about himself; he doesn't downplay his accomplishments, but neither is he bragging about them.

Title: Gone Tomorrow (Jack Reacher, #13)
Author: Lee Child
My Review: 4.5/5 - Wish I could remember where I got this book recommendation from. It's as if Tom Clancy wrote a mystery novel!

Title: The Immortal Iron Fist, Volume 1: The Last Iron Fist Story
Author: Ed Brubaker
Additional Authors: Matt Fraction, David Aja, Travel Foreman, Duane Swierczynski, John Severin, Russ Heath, Tonci Zonjic, Sal Buscema, Kano, Tom Palmer, Guisseppe Cammuncoli, Matt Hollingsworth, Patrick Zircher
My Review: I might pick up the Immoral Iron Fist compilation tradeback. Really liked the artistic style, although this volume barely gets into any actual plot.

Title: Blood Music
Author: Greg Bear
My Review: Greatly enjoyed the premise, although the end was a bit lacking for me.

Title: A Few Seconds of Panic: A 5-Foot-8, 170-Pound, 43-Year-Old Sportswriter Plays in the NFL
Author: Stefan Fatsis
My Review: Exactly what you'd expect. I especially enjoyed reading about the wide range of players in the NFL, and what they thought about fans, the organization, playing football, etc.

Title: Resonance
Author: Chris Dolley
My Review: Actually 3.5 stars. Enjoyed the premise, although some parts were a bit far-fetched.

Title: Fool Moon (The Dresden Files, #2)
Author: Jim Butcher
My Review: I'm enjoying the Dresden Files quite a lot. Pulpy fantasy-mystery for the win!

Title: Eternity (The Way, #2)
Author: Greg Bear
My Review: Similar to the first book, I really enjoyed the experience of reading Eternity. However, opposite of Eon, the plot and ending seemed quite contrived. 3.5/4.

Title: Storm Front (The Dresden Files, #1)
Author: Jim Butcher
My Review: Pulpy fantasy mystery. What's not to like? 3.5 stars.

Title: Eon (The Way, #1)
Author: Greg Bear
My Review: Really liked it as I was reading, but at the end, I was left a little unsatisfied. Loved the SF aspect, but the plot was lacking. 3.5 stars.

Title: The Caryatids
Author: Bruce Sterling
My Review: Actually a 2.5. I enjoyed some of the concepts while I was reading, but it didn't really go anywhere.

Title: A Long Way Gone: Memoirs of a Boy Soldier
Author: Ishmael Beah
My Review: Even after reading the book, it's hard to comprehend the horrors that Ishmael went through. The author pulls no punches in telling the story of becoming a boy soldier and what he went through in the Sierra Leone unrest.

Title: Starburst
Author: Frederik Pohl
My Review: I read a short story that was excerpted from this book. As it turns out, I loved that way more than the full-length novel.

Title: Self-Made Man: One Woman's Journey Into Manhood and Back Again
Author: Norah Vincent
My Review: An interesting look at the male world from a female perspective.

Title: On Writing Well: The Classic Guide to Writing Nonfiction
Author: William Zinsser

Title: The Race For A New Game Machine: Creating the Chips Inside the XBox and the Playstation 3
Author: David Shippy
My Review: I enjoyed reading this book. David Shippy (what an appropriate name!) tells the story of developing the processors behind the PS3 and Xbox 360. There's not too much detail, which is appreciated, since the little that he did go over was beyond my ken. Overall, a quick and fun read. The most interesting bit for me was seeing how Microsoft beat Sony to market.

Title: Daemon (Daemon, #1)
Author: Daniel Suarez
My Review: Would be a 4.5/5 if GR supported half-stars. Daemon's an incredibly fun read, especially for the geeky. There's a strong undercurrent of nerdy wish-fulfillment, and the book requires quite a bit of suspension of disbelief, but I can live with that. Despite that, I enjoyed the ride, and can't wait for the next book.

Title: Mastering Regular Expressions
Author: Jeffrey E.F. Friedl
My Review: I thought I was pretty good at regular expressions, but this book puts me to shame. It also makes me glad that I don't have to worry about optimizing them or using them for anything besides quick REPL-type things. Fantastic for anyone who does need a deeper knowledge of regexen. Still quite good for people at my level, where more technical knowledge is helpful, even if it isn't necessary.

Title: American Lion: Andrew Jackson in the White House
Author: Jon Meacham
My Review: It has potential, but I don't have enough interest in American history and/or Andrew Jackson to finish it.

Title: Caine Black Knife (The Acts of Caine, #3)
Author: Matthew Woodring Stover
My Review: The first book was by far the best, but I enjoyed Caine Black Knife more than Blade of Tyshalle. The plot is simpler, and it's nice to get both more advancing of the present day story while reading about the adventure that made him Caine.

Title: Heroes Die (The Acts of Caine, #1)
Author: Matthew Woodring Stover
My Review: A fantastic read. Actually 4.5/5, and comes damn close to getting 5 stars from me. Everything was terrific, from the universe to the characters. I even enjoyed the touches of meta-fiction, which were just enough to pique my whimsy and not too much to be overbearing. Loved this through and through. There was one aspect towards the end that jarred a little, but not nearly enough as to spoil my enjoyment of the book.

Title: By Schism Rent Asunder (Safehold, #2)
Author: David Weber
My Review: Lots and lots of setup for the third book. There didn't really seem to be any overarching plot threads, but Weber's moving people and countries around. Not too much shakeup in the status quo. I am looking forward to the next book, though.

Title: Blade of Tyshalle (The Acts of Caine, #2)
Author: Matthew Woodring Stover
My Review: Not as good as Heroes Die, but still pretty awesome. I don't think the plot was as tight as in the first book.

Title: Off Armageddon Reef (Safehold, #1)
Author: David Weber
My Review:
It's exactly what I expected from Weber. He does what he does best, which is wide-scale political intrigue with a strong military background. The universe premise is SF, although the actual book is much more fantasy than anything else. Much like the Prince Roger series, a medieval civilization is greatly advanced by an outsider with vastly more technical knowledge. In fact, the whole naval emphasis gave me an eerie sense of deja-vu, as it parallels much of the March to the Stars "uplift".

As usual, the grand plot and military actions are the strengths of this book. The characters are standard, with the usual Weber do-gooders and villains. And of course, there is a deluge of characters thrown at you straightaway. They all have incomprehensible names that look alike, which made the book much harder to get into. After the clean writing in Heroes Die, it took a while to get into Off Armageddon Reef, but once I was re-accustomed to Weber's style, it was smooth sailing.

Title: Soon I Will Be Invincible
Author: Austin Grossman
My Review: A pleasure to read, although the ending was lackluster. More like 3.5/5, if I could do half-ratings.

Title: His Majesty's Dragon (Temeraire, #1)
Author: Naomi Novik
My Review: Good, except for the deus ex machina at the climax.

Title: March to the Stars (Empire of Man, #3)
Author: David Weber

Title: Birth of Fire
Author: Jerry Pournelle
My Review: Eh. I've read better.

Title: March to the Sea (Empire of Man, #2)
Author: David Weber
My Review: After reading March Upcountry, I had to continue on with the tale. Thought this was a bit weaker than the first book, but still enjoyable nonetheless. Now I want to finish the trilogy.

Title: March Upcountry (Empire of Man, #1)
Author: David Weber
My Review: Pulpy SF, what can I say? An easy and fun read.

Title: Implied Spaces
Author: Walter Jon Williams
My Review: An enjoyable read. Fun venture into an almost-Singularity era, but I didn't really feel that it utilized the universe as much as it should have. The wormholes and created universes were interesting ideas, but I wanted a bit more.

Title: Moneyball: The Art of Winning an Unfair Game
Author: Michael   Lewis
My Review: Sports, statistics, and exploiting inefficiencies. Everything this book is about interests me. Having it be well-written as well is just icing on the cake. I love the use of math to find diamonds in the rough. I also very much enjoy using statistic to debunk accepted knowledge.

Title: Them: Adventures with Extremists
Author: Jon Ronson
My Review: The subject matter didn't interest me enough to keep me hooked. The writing itself was fine, but I wasn't really expecting a book about conspiracy theorists.

Title: Traffic: Why We Drive the Way We Do and What It Says About Us
Author: Tom Vanderbilt
My Review: What I learned... judgment of risk and safety involve many, many contradictions. Overall, lots of interesting facts and statistics, but kind of hard to read.

Title: Stories of Your Life and Others
Author: Ted Chiang
My Review: I didn't realize I'd read one of his short stories before (Hell Is the Absence of God). Great reads, all of them. Fast reads too, being short stories. Would get 4.5/5 if goodreads had half-stars.

Title: The Guns of the South
Author: Harry Turtledove
My Review: This book surely has the most absurd concept: a hate group goes back in time and gives Robert E. Lee AK-47s. And yet, Turtledove does a remarkable job with the characters and the story, making it pretty hard to put down. A great read, and one that makes me want to read up on Civil War history. Somewhat more serious than my usual SF reads, and really incredible that such a strange premise could yield such a good book.

Title: The Inner Game of Tennis: The Classic Guide to the Mental Side of Peak Performance
Author: W. Timothy Gallwey
My Review: I definitely agree with the core concepts espoused by this book. In short, let your subconscious (the author calls this "Self 2") do the work. Lots of good stuff in here on getting your conscious mind out of the way. I'm not entirely convinced that you should let go completely, but the author might say that's my "Self 1" talking. Perhaps that's the case. Some of the book felt a bit "woo"-ish, but overall, I enjoyed it a lot. Very easy to read, and left me with a bunch of thoughts on how to teach.

Title: Mindless Eating: Why We Eat More Than We Think
Author: Brian Wansink
My Review: A great book to read for anyone interested in the psychology of eating. As with many subjects, it's amazing how little control people have over the act of eating and feeling full. I don't need to lose weight myself, but I find myself rather curious about the "dieting" tactics espoused by the book. They make a lot of sense, and seem way safer than the fad diets floating around nowadays.

Title: The Elements of Graphic Design: Space, Unity, Page Architecture, and Type
Author: Alex W. White
My Review: Yet another book that I wish my coworkers would read. This is written at just about the perfect level for me, covering a broad amount of content without going too deep. It was a good overview, and definitely showed me that I could stand to learn some more about this topic. (Especially typography, which was quite fascinating. I've read a bit about typography in the past, but this presented the topic in pretty much the exact amount of detail that I wanted.)

Title: Ageless Spine, Lasting Health: The Open Secret to Pain-Free Living and Comfortable Aging
Author: Kathleen Porter
My Review: Not nearly as useful as I had hoped. Overall, it made sense, even if it had some "woo" in it, but I wasn't terribly impressed.

Title: How to Wrap Five More Eggs: Traditional Japanese Packaging
Author: Hideyuki Oka
My Review: I don't really know how to start reviewing this book. It's really just a huge book of pictures of Japanese packaging. As I read it (if the act of looking at each picture could be called reading), I would be struck by the design of a package every so often, but I skimmed through much of the book not knowing what the package was for. There is an appendix of sorts at the end explaining the pictures, but I really wish the blurbs had been included with the pictures. So, I guess it's pretty nifty, but not nifty enough for me to flip back and forth between picture and appendix. If the blurbs had been nearer the pictures, I probably would've given this another star.

Title: Nation
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review: I was waffling between rating this a four or five. But I think I like it enough that it gets the full five stars. It was simple to read, being YA, but not overly so. I liked the mix of simplicity and depth, even if the depth was somewhat limited. I just really enjoyed the act of reading this novel.

Title: NextWave: Agents of H.A.T.E., Vol. 2: I Kick Your Face
Author: Warren Ellis
Additional Authors: Stuart Immonen, Wade Von Grawbadger, Dave McCaig

Title: NextWave: Agents of H.A.T.E., Vol. 1: This is What They Want
Author: Warren Ellis
Additional Authors: Stuart Immonen, Wade Von Grawbadger, Dave McCaig

Title: Why Popcorn Costs So Much at the Movies: And Other Pricing Puzzles
Author: Richard B. McKenzie
My Review: Kind of interesting, but rather dry. There's some good stuff in the book, but I liked The Undercover Economist better.

Title: Presentation Zen: Simple Ideas on Presentation Design and Delivery
Author: Garr Reynolds
My Review: Being at Microsoft, I've seen my fair share of crappy presentations. Anyone giving a presentation should be forced to read this book.

Title: How to Break a Terrorist: The U.S. Interrogators Who Used Brains, Not Brutality, to Take Down the Deadliest Man in Iraq
Author: Matthew Alexander
My Review: Not exactly what I was expecting, but still interesting in its own right. I though this would be more about facts and policies, but it turned out to be a story of how the author helped catch one of the major terrorists in Iraq. (Really, "How I Broke Terrorists" would have been a more accurate title.) Pretty easy and fun to read.

Title: The Stepsister Scheme (Princess, #1)
Author: Jim C. Hines
My Review: A fun read. Uses the original forms of the fairy tales, which I somehow knew of already. (Perhaps from Fables? I forget.) Kind of interesting, but not really fleshed out enough for my liking.

Title: Beautiful Code: Leading Programmers Explain How They Think
Author: Andy Oram
Additional Authors: Greg Wilson, Jon L. Bentley, Brian W. Kernighan, Charles Petzold, Douglas Crockford, Henry S. Warren Jr., Ashish Gulhati, Lincoln Stein, Jim Kent, Jack Dongarra, Poitr Luszczek, Adam Kolawa, Greg Kroah-Hartman, Diomidis Spinellis, Andrew Kuchling, Travis E. Oliphant, Ronald Mak, Rogério Atem de Carvalho, Rafael Monnerat, Bryan Cantrill, Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat, Simon Peyton Jones, R. Kent Dybuig, William R. Otte, Douglas C. Schmidt, Andrew Patzer, Karl Fogel, Tim Bray, Elliotte Rusty Harold, Michael C. Feathers, Alberto Savoia
My Review: Not as good as I had hoped, although there are a few gems between the covers. There's a lot of actual code in this book though, so be prepared to do some serious reading and thinking should you pick it up. Overall, it was fun to read, but I'm not sure how much I took away.

Title: The Black Hole War: My Battle with Stephen Hawking to Make the World Safe for Quantum Mechanics
Author: Leonard Susskind
My Review: I enjoyed reading this, although Susskind lost me about 3/4ths of the way through. As always, I like seeing what's going on in modern physics, even if it goes way over my head. However, the tone seemed a bit awkward at times, and it seemed to me that Susskind has a chip on his shoulder from arguing with the other physicists.

Title: In Defense of Food: An Eater's Manifesto
Author: Michael Pollan
My Review: Didn't really learn anything new, but Pollan's thoughts on food mostly match up with my own. It's mostly a deeper look at the ideas he put forth in the NYT article a little while back. I don't disagree with much of what he says, and this is would be a good summary for those who want to look into his "Eat food. Not too much. Only plants" suggestion.

Title: Outliers: The Story of Success
Author: Malcolm Gladwell
My Review: Posits that culture and circumstances plays a large part in how people turn out. Makes sense. Pretty quick and easy read, much like Blink was. Lots of interesting data points and stuff to think about.

Title: Anathem
Author: Neal Stephenson
My Review: Almost a little too long and dense to give five stars, but definitely better than four stars. Really enjoyed the book, with tons of interesting ideas and a very satisfying finish. I found it surprisingly fun to figure out the meaning of the made-up words, but it's incredibly annoying to keep a mental dictionary of them while reading. Still, I enjoyed the finish and the ideas, and really, that's mostly what I ask for from SF.

Title: No Cure for the Paladin Blues (The Order of the Stick, #2)
Author: Rich Burlew
My Review: Makes me want to re-read the first two volumes of OotS. (I really dig the acronym, too...)

Title: Panic in Level 4: Cannibals, Killer Viruses, and Other Journeys to the Edge of Science
Author: Richard   Preston
My Review: Started out great, but was less interesting than I had expected. For some reason, I did not think this was a series of essays, and I guess I prefer his full-length books instead. Still, pretty quick reads, and most of the essays/shorts are pretty interesting.

Title: All the Rules: Time-Tested Secrets for Capturing the Heart of Mr. Right
Author: Ellen Fein
My Review: This book was hilarious. It was actually kind of fun to read, in a WTF sort of way. Recommended for those who need a good laugh.

Title: The Best Software Writing I: Selected and Introduced by Joel Spolsky
Author: Joel Spolsky
My Review: I've actually read a bunch of these essays on the intarwebs, but they're extremely well written and worth re-reading. I'd actually rate it 4.5/5. Well worth reading for any programmer, but I wouldn't say it's a must-read.
